r:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Acknowledgments</span></div><div data-state="closed" data-orientation="vertical" data-slot="accordion-item" class="border-foreground/10 last:border-b-0 border-b-0"><h3 data-orientation="vertical" data-state="closed" class="flex"><button type="button" aria-controls="radix-_R_6banpfqt6btb_" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" data-orientation="vertical" id="radix-_R_2banpfqt6btb_" data-slot="accordion-trigger" class="focus-visible:border-ring focus-visible:ring-ring/50 flex flex-1 items-start justify-between gap-4 rounded-md text-left transition-all outline-none focus-visible:ring-[3px] disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 [&amp;[data-state=open]&gt;svg]:rotate-180 w-full py-0.75 font-light text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer" data-radix-collection-item=""><span class="line-clamp-2">Introduction</span><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-chevron-down text-muted-foreground pointer-events-none size-4 shrink-0 translate-y-0.5 transition-transform duration-200"><path d="m6 9 6 6 6-6"></path></svg></button></h3><div data-state="closed" id="radix-_R_6banpfqt6btb_" hidden="" role="region" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2banpfqt6btb_" data-orientation="vertical" data-slot="accordion-content" class="data-[state=closed]:animate-accordion-up data-[state=open]:animate-accordion-down overflow-hidden text-sm" style="--radix-accordion-content-height:var(--radix-collapsible-content-height);--radix-accordion-content-width:var(--radix-collapsible-content-width)"></div></div></div><div data-orientation="horizontal" role="none" class="shrink-0 bg-border h-[1px] w-full my-4"></div><div data-slot="accordion" class="" data-orientation="vertical"><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2 font-bold">The Translation</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Colophon</span></div></div><div data-orientation="horizontal" role="none" class="shrink-0 bg-border h-[1px] w-full my-4"></div><div data-slot="accordion" class="" data-orientation="vertical"><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Notes</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Glossary</span></div><div class="w-full py-0.75 font-light leading-5 text-sm hover:text-foreground/40 hover:no-underline hover:cursor-pointer"><span class="line-clamp-2">Bibliography</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>$RS=function(a,b){a=document.getElementById(a);b=document.getElementById(b);for(a.parentNode.removeChild(a);a.firstChild;)b.parentNode.insertBefore(a.firstChild,b);b.parentNode.removeChild(b)};$RS("S:3","P:3")</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"1f:I[411156,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBackMatterPanel\"]\n20:T511,\u003cp\u003eIn Buddhist literature, this is an epithet applied to buddhas, most often to Śākyamuni. The Sanskrit term generally means “possessing fortune,” but in specifically Buddhist contexts it implies that a buddha is in possession of six auspicious qualities (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e) associated with complete awakening. The Tibetan term‍—where \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebcom\u003c/em\u003e is said to refer to “subduing” the four māras, \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eldan\u003c/em\u003e to “possessing” the great qualities of buddhahood, and \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e’das\u003c/em\u003e to “going beyond” saṃsāra and nirvāṇa‍—possibly reflects the commentarial tradition where the Sanskrit \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e is interpreted, in addition, as “one who destroys the four māras.” This is achieved either by reading \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagavat\u003c/em\u003e as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhagnavat\u003c/em\u003e (“one who broke”), or by tracing the word \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003ebhaga\u003c/em\u003e to the root \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003e√bhañj\u003c/em\u003e (“to break”).\u003c/p\u003e21:T58e,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eThe term is used to designate a senior monk. The sixteen great \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-54\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e, or sixteen noble \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003eelders\u003c/span\u003e (\u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eāryasthavira\u003c/em\u003e), were the successors of the Buddha’s teaching after he passed. They promised to preserve the teaching until the coming of the future Buddha Maitreya. They are on the path of seeing of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-54\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e path. Each \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-54\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e lived in a specific place: (1) Aṅgaja on Mt. Kailash; (2) \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-91\"\u003eAjita\u003c/span\u003e in the Crystal Wood of Sages; (3) Vanavāsin on Mt. Saptaparṇa; (4) Mahākālika in Tāmradvīpa; (5) Vajrīputra in Siṃhaladvīpa; (6) Śrībhadra on Yamunādvīpa; (7) Kanakavatsa in Kashmir; (8) Kanakabharadvāja in the western continent of Godānīya; (9) Bakula in the northern continent of Uttarakuru; (10) \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-84\"\u003eRāhula\u003c/span\u003e in Priyaṅgudvīpa; (11) \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\"UT22084-051-003-81\"\u003eCūḍapanthaka\u003c/span\u003e on Mt. Gṛdhrakūṭa; (12) Piṇḍolabharadvāja in the eastern continent of Pūrvavideha; (13) Mahāpanthaka in Trayatriṃśa; (14) Nāgasena on Mt. \u003cspan class=\"ignore\"\u003eMeru\u003c/span\u003e; (15) Gopaka on Mt. Bhihula; and (16) Abhedya in the Himālayas.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"22:T754,"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eOne of the first Buddhist monasteries, located in a park outside Śrāvastī, the capital of the ancient kingdom of Kośala in northern India. This park was originally owned by Prince Jeta, hence the name Jetavana, meaning Jeta’s grove. The wealthy merchant Anāthapiṇḍada, wishing to offer it to the Buddha, sought to buy it from him, but the prince, not wishing to sell, said he would only do so if Anāthapiṇḍada covered the entire property with gold coins. Anāthapiṇḍada agreed, and managed to cover all of the park except the entrance, hence the name Anāthapiṇḍadasyārāmaḥ, meaning Anāthapiṇḍada’s park. The place is usually referred to in the sūtras as “Jetavana, Anāthapiṇḍada’s park,” and according to the \u003ccite class=\"title break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eSaṃghabhedavastu \u003c/cite\u003e the Buddha used Prince Jeta’s name in first place because that was Prince Jeta’s own unspoken wish while Anāthapiṇḍada was offering the park. Inspired by the occasion and the Buddha’s use of his name, Prince Jeta then offered the rest of the property and had an entrance gate built. The Buddha specifically instructed those who recite the sūtras to use Prince Jeta’s name in first place to commemorate the mutual effort of both benefactors. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp class=\"definition\"\u003eAnāthapiṇḍada built residences for the monks, to house them during the monsoon season, thus creating the first Buddhist monastery. It was one of the Buddha’s main residences, where he spent around nineteen rainy season retreats, and it was therefore the setting for many of the Buddha’s discourses and events. According to the travel accounts of Chinese monks, it was still in use as a Buddhist monastery in the early fifth century \u003cspan class=\"small-caps\"\u003eᴄᴇ\u003c/span\u003e, but by the sixth century it had been reduced to ruins. \u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"23:T456,\u003cp\u003eA frequently used synonym for \u003cem class=\"emph\"\u003ebuddha\u003c/em\u003e. According to different explanations, it can be read as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-gata\u003c/em\u003e, literally meaning “one who has thus gone,” or as \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003etathā-āgata\u003c/em\u003e, “one who has thus come.” \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eGata\u003c/em\u003e, though literally meaning “gone,” is a past passive participle used to describe a state or condition of existence. \u003cem class=\"foreign break text-sa\" lang=\"sa-LATN\"\u003eTatha­(tā)\u003c/em\u003e, often rendered as “suchness” or “thusness,” is the quality or condition of things as they really are, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms. Therefore, this epithet is interpreted in different ways, but in general it implies one who has departed in the wake of the buddhas of the past, or one who has manifested the supreme awakening dependent on the reality that does not abide in the two extremes of existence and quiescence. It is also often used as a specific epithet of the Buddha Śākyamuni.\u003c/p\u003e"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"18:[\"$\",\"$L1f\",null,{\"abbreviations\":[],\"bibliography\":[{\"heading\":\"Tibetan Texts\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"13157476-771c-42e0-ac1e-4afe042e89d1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003e’phags pa bde ba can gyi bkod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e. Toh 115, Degé Kangyur vol. 51 (mdo sde, ja), folios 195.b–200.b. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"5e73ac8e-7b8b-4a36-8409-bf226d470b6c\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003e’phags pa bde ba can gyi bkod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\u003c/em\u003e. bka’ ’gyur (dpe bsdur ma) [Comparative Edition of the Kangyur], krung go’i bod rig pa zhib ’jug ste gnas kyi bka’ bstan dpe sdur khang (The Tibetan Tripitaka Collation Bureau of the China Tibetology Research Center). 108 volumes. Beijing: krung go’i bod rig pa dpe skrun khang (China Tibetology Publishing House), 2006–9, vol. 51, pp. 532–42. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"71dd1ef8-c7be-43c2-9fc0-d9a79dcfd036\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHa’o wun zhon and To’u tshun chi, eds. \u003cem\u003ebod rgya shan sbyar gyi shes bya’i rnam grangs kun btus tshig mdzod\u003c/em\u003e. Beijing: mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Minorities Publishing House), 1987. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"af4e9517-f090-45f5-8086-7f9f182882a3\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003ebde smon phyogs bsgrigs\u003c/em\u003e [\u003cem\u003eThe Collection of Prayers for Sukhāvatī\u003c/em\u003e]. Chengdu: si khron mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Sichuan Minorities Publishing House), 2007.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"b7da1c0e-95fb-4ac2-b8ad-199c916d4e89\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003emkhas grub rā ga a syas mdzad pa’i rnam dag bde chen zhing gi smon lam\u003c/em\u003e [\u003cem\u003eLong Prayer for Sukhāvatī\u003c/em\u003e]. Chengdu: si khron mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Sichuan Minorities Publishing House), 2007.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"a9a2cda0-117f-4c41-b3db-d469776ebbe1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003e’phags pa bzang po spyod pa’i smon lam gyi rgyal po\u003c/em\u003e [\u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"https://read.84000.co/translation/toh1095.html\\\"\u003eThe Noble King of Prayers of Good Conduct\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e]. Toh 1095, Degé Kangyur, vol. 101 (gzungs ’dus, waM), folios 262.a–266.b.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Sanskrit Texts\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"e6ac3f44-7544-4d1c-9fc4-75a9a70037ec\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003e \u003cem\u003eĀrya­sukhāvatī­vyūha­nāma­mahā­yāna­sūtra\u003c/em\u003e. \u003ca href=\\\"http://gretil.sub.uni-goettingen.de/gretil/1_sanskr/4_rellit/buddh/sukhvysu.htm\\\"\u003ehttp://gretil.sub.uni-goettingen.de\u003c/a\u003e. Accessed August 25, 2010.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]},{\"heading\":\"Secondary Literature\",\"entries\":[{\"uuid\":\"873b2a46-fee1-422b-9b50-0f5e46892114\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eEpstein, Ronald, trans. \u003cem\u003eThe Amitābha Sūtra\u003c/em\u003e. Hsüan Hua, A General Explanation of the Buddha Speaks of Amitābha Sūtra. San Francisco: Buddhist Text Translation Society, 1974. \u003ca href=\\\"http://online.sfsu.edu/~rone/Buddhism/amitabha.htm\\\"\u003eonline.sfsu.ed\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"bbe6c22e-0b04-49ee-8ec4-d997b654f8d7\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eFujita, Kōtatsu. “Textual Origins of the \u003cem\u003eKuan Wu-liang-shou ching\u003c/em\u003e.” In \u003cem\u003eChinese Buddhist Apocrypha\u003c/em\u003e, edited by Robert E. Buswell, Jr., 149–173. Honolulu: University of Hawai’i Press, 1990.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"a58252d0-1ddd-4b36-82d4-2ce89cba7f58\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eGomez, Luis O. \u003cem\u003eLand of Bliss: The Paradise of the Buddha of Measureless Light; Sanskrit and Chinese Versions of the Sukhāvatīvyūha Sūtras.\u003c/em\u003e Honolulu: University of Hawai’i Press, 1996.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"c05c270c-0f39-4789-b9e7-d459342c7cf1\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eHapatsch, Hischam A., trans. and ed. \u003cem\u003eDie Heiligen Schriften des Amitābha-Buddhismus: Das große Sukhāvatī-vyūha-Sūtra, Das kleine Sukhāvatī-vyūha-Sūtra, Das Meditationssūtra\u003c/em\u003e. Berlin, 2007. \u003ca href=\\\"http://www.littera.de/buecher/sukha.html\\\"\u003ewww.littera.de\u003c/a\u003e. Accessed 2010.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"673a54ff-8f89-4e1a-8c15-8645b1885093\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eMüller, Max, and Bunyiu Nanjio, trans. “Āryasukhāvatīvyūhasūtra.” \u003cem\u003eAnecdota Oxoniensia: Aryan Series\u003c/em\u003e. Vol. I, part II. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1883.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"187d3c3b-13ad-4feb-a277-10a496c54154\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eNakamura, Hajime. \u003cem\u003eIndian Buddhism: A Survey with Bibliographical Notes\u003c/em\u003e. Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass Publications, 1987.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"ac744700-8796-4c67-be00-187e3dc109f9\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eRoberts, Peter Alan and Emily Bower, trans. \u003cem\u003e\u003ca href=\\\"http://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-054-003.html\\\"\u003eThe Aparimitāyurjñāna Sūtra\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/em\u003e (Toh 674). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2016. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null},{\"uuid\":\"ca545715-4004-426a-9283-ef8199f9cd6f\",\"html\":\"\u003cp\u003eUtsuki, Nishu. \u003cem\u003eThe Smaller Sukhāvatīvyūha Sūtra or The Sūtra on the Buddha Amitāyus: Translated from the Chinese Version of Kumārajīva\u003c/em\u003e. Kyoto: Educational Department of the West Hongwanji, 1924. \u003ca href=\\\"http://web.mit.edu/stclair/www/smaller.html\\\"\u003eweb.mit.edu\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"workUuid\":null}]}],\"endnotes\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"edc71339-e581-4b0a-b812-32ea0454ffd1\",\"sort\":825,\"type\":\"endnotesHeader\",\"label\":\"n.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":5,\"uuid\":\"6b8476a3-8e65-43be-b704-8f26d7efdbd5\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Notes\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":5}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ae7451ca-8305-41a6-93bb-33367b887e02\",\"sort\":827,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.1\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī is the shortest of three sūtras that expound the Land of Delight, the pure realm of Amitābha, called Sukhāvatī. The Kangyur includes Tibetan translations of two of these texts: this one, often called the “shorter” Sukhāvatī, and the “longer” sūtra, with the formal title The Array of Amitābha (Toh 49 in the Heap of Jewels section). The third, The Amitāyus Meditation Sūtra, is only extant in Chinese. The shorter sūtra, according to the Sanskrit scholar Luis Gomez, first appeared in its written form during the first century ᴄᴇ, possibly in what was then Northwest India and is now Pakistan.\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"5dcadeea-8654-43cf-997f-acf495558f40\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-3\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":229,\"uuid\":\"ae7451ca-8305-41a6-93bb-33367b887e02\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Toh 49 (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":8}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’od dpag med kyi bkod pa’i mdo\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":38},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":8,\"end\":38,\"uuid\":\"1d82d1ca-5f53-4115-b66c-34462b7febe9\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":38,\"end\":40}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha­vyūha­sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":60,\"uuid\":\"fd8b84c0-0a73-4032-86cc-ffe611da4ef4\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), also known in Tibetan as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":88}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bde ba can gyi zhing\u2028 bkod pa’i bstan pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":128},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a0fea3ff-794f-4f09-9778-3b535df35e44\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":128,\"end\":130}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Teaching on the Display of the Pure Land\u2028 of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":130,\"end\":188},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2789590c-504b-48a4-ba80-8f6a1a5ece14\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") or, informally, the “longer” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":188,\"end\":219}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":219,\"end\":228},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9645afdf-7399-460d-be16-1e0b9413b130\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\",\"start\":219,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"0d51a86c-9a94-4bfe-a9dd-caa1f4ae7651\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":228,\"end\":229}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ba07f770-0540-44e8-acd5-d6eae8b29962\",\"sort\":840,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.2\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī is the shortest of three sūtras that expound the Land of Delight, the pure realm of Amitābha, called Sukhāvatī. The Kangyur includes Tibetan translations of two of these texts: this one, often called the “shorter” Sukhāvatī, and the “longer” sūtra, with the formal title The Array of Amitābha (Toh 49 in the Heap of Jewels section). The third, The Amitāyus Meditation Sūtra, is only extant in Chinese. The shorter sūtra, according to the Sanskrit scholar Luis Gomez, first appeared in its written form during the first century ᴄᴇ, possibly in what was then Northwest India and is now Pakistan.\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"5dcadeea-8654-43cf-997f-acf495558f40\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-3\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":457,\"uuid\":\"ba07f770-0540-44e8-acd5-d6eae8b29962\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The latter sūtra’s Sanskrit title, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitāyur­dhyāna­sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":56},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"493a9397-e3da-4af4-9822-014c4a8ce7b0\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", is now believed to have been fabricated at a later date. Most academic scholars believe that the extant text of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":56,\"end\":174}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Guan wu liang shou jing\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":174,\"end\":197},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"14790826-4a08-4e52-adf7-ab3cb8a003a3\",\"lang\":\"Zh-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was compiled either in Central Asia or China. See Fujita (1990), especially p. 155 and n. 48, on the question of its title. On p. 155 Fujita says, “It cannot be determined categorically what the Sanskrit title of the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":197,\"end\":415}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Kuan Wu-liang-shou ching\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":415,\"end\":439},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"47f08e2f-02f3-4e23-9098-a4342957884e\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" might have been.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":439,\"end\":457}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cd485805-f6b1-40bb-9141-5ff6d5f50972\",\"sort\":848,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.3\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī is the shortest of three sūtras that expound the Land of Delight, the pure realm of Amitābha, called Sukhāvatī. The Kangyur includes Tibetan translations of two of these texts: this one, often called the “shorter” Sukhāvatī, and the “longer” sūtra, with the formal title The Array of Amitābha (Toh 49 in the Heap of Jewels section). The third, The Amitāyus Meditation Sūtra, is only extant in Chinese. The shorter sūtra, according to the Sanskrit scholar Luis Gomez, first appeared in its written form during the first century ᴄᴇ, possibly in what was then Northwest India and is now Pakistan.\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"5dcadeea-8654-43cf-997f-acf495558f40\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-3\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21,\"uuid\":\"cd485805-f6b1-40bb-9141-5ff6d5f50972\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Gomez (1996), p. xii.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":21}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"16121895-52e7-4e90-b153-afcbf36b9d75\",\"sort\":850,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.4\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"A Sanskrit version of the smaller Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī is extant today, as well as Tibetan and Chinese translations. All the translations show some variation from the Sanskrit source in content and style, which can be attributed in part to cultural and geographic conditions in Tibet and China. The translations have become more influential than the original itself, for which we presently lack any contextual information.\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"sort\":60,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"5a80817c-1d1c-48af-a59c-13a2898460a0\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-4\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"16121895-52e7-4e90-b153-afcbf36b9d75\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Nakamura (1987), p. 204.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"da8db36e-72fc-4ec6-8500-69586f52842c\",\"sort\":852,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.5\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"There are several Chinese translations of this sūtra, dating from between 240 and 400 ᴄᴇ, but only one Tibetan version, translated in the eighth or ninth century. The Chinese versions of the sūtra spread through China, Korea, Japan, and Vietnam and played an important role in the formation of the Pure Land schools in these countries. These versions appear to embellish the description of the wonders of the realm of Sukhāvatī, whereas the Tibetan version is more subdued and shows its main variations from the Sanskrit original in the names and the number of buddhas presiding over the different buddha realms. The various editions in the Tibetan canon, i.e., the Degé, Narthang, Peking, and Lhasa editions, show no major differences that would alter any meaning.\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"sort\":66,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"75d6cc52-a859-4d2d-9fc6-e92fc6d80d65\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-5\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24,\"uuid\":\"da8db36e-72fc-4ec6-8500-69586f52842c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Nakamura (1987), p. 206.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":24}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"4be4c72e-7d7c-40ff-ade4-7cbb35e1ffe8\",\"sort\":854,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.6\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"The sūtra’s overall subject is revealed in the title. The Sanskrit term sukhāvatī, in Tibetan Dewachen (bde ba can), designates a realm of delight, a place where no suffering is experienced. The inhabitants of this realm are spiritually advanced beings who enjoy the presence of buddhas, bodhisattvas, and arhats, and engage exclusively in wholesome activities. The principal buddha of this realm has two names, Amitāyus (Limitless Life) and Amitābha (Limitless Light). Even though it is not explicitly stated in this particular sūtra, Amitāyus is, in Vajrayāna contexts, sometimes considered a sambhogakāya form of Buddha Amitābha. The term vyūha (Tib. bkod pa) means “display,” indicating that the sūtra is to a large extent a description of this buddha realm and its characteristics. It is a land with lakes and forests full of jewels, with magical birds, and with little bells producing lovely sounds. Its ideal environment enhances the spiritual practice of Sukhāvatī’s inhabitants.\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"sort\":85,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"uuid\":\"0f0d0877-a783-4bc1-a1f3-966e37f2a5d6\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-8\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":92,\"uuid\":\"4be4c72e-7d7c-40ff-ade4-7cbb35e1ffe8\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"But see also Roberts and Bower (2016), Introduction, on the conflation of these two buddhas.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":92}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f1582114-fa6e-47e2-b232-53e3b09ceb50\",\"sort\":856,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.7\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to all the buddhas and bodhisattvas. Thus did I hear at one time. The Bhagavān was dwelling in Śrāvastī, in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park, along with a large monastic saṅgha of 1,250 bhikṣus, all of them great elders, śrāvakas, and arhats, such as the elder Śāriputra, Mahā­maudgalyāyana, Mahākāśyapa, Mahā­kātyāyana, Mahākapphiṇa, Mahākauṣṭhila, Revata, Śuddhipaṃthaka, Nanda, Ānanda, Rāhula, Gavāṃpati, Bharadvāja, Kālodāyin, Vakula, and Aniruddha. He dwelt with these and other great śrāvakas and with many bodhisattva mahāsattvas, such as the youthful Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Ajita, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Gandhahastin, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Nityodyukta, and the bodhisattva mahāsattva Anikṣiptadhura, along with many other bodhisattva mahāsattvas. He was also accompanied by Śakra, the lord of gods, and Brahmā, the ruler of the Sahā world, along with many myriads of gods.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":206,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7f12c74e-7191-42d0-8d7f-a89ce8dcf714\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-14\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":150,\"uuid\":\"f1582114-fa6e-47e2-b232-53e3b09ceb50\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit has “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"abhijñānābhijñātaiḥ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":37},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":18,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"e10e26b8-e7e8-4f48-8ac9-a686358f1a64\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"”, i.e., “bhikṣus, all of them proficient in the [five kinds of] superknowledge.” This is omitted in the Tibetan.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":150}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a3a439ab-23c3-4668-8b5b-c23d3151999c\",\"sort\":860,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.8\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to all the buddhas and bodhisattvas. Thus did I hear at one time. The Bhagavān was dwelling in Śrāvastī, in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park, along with a large monastic saṅgha of 1,250 bhikṣus, all of them great elders, śrāvakas, and arhats, such as the elder Śāriputra, Mahā­maudgalyāyana, Mahākāśyapa, Mahā­kātyāyana, Mahākapphiṇa, Mahākauṣṭhila, Revata, Śuddhipaṃthaka, Nanda, Ānanda, Rāhula, Gavāṃpati, Bharadvāja, Kālodāyin, Vakula, and Aniruddha. He dwelt with these and other great śrāvakas and with many bodhisattva mahāsattvas, such as the youthful Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Ajita, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Gandhahastin, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Nityodyukta, and the bodhisattva mahāsattva Anikṣiptadhura, along with many other bodhisattva mahāsattvas. He was also accompanied by Śakra, the lord of gods, and Brahmā, the ruler of the Sahā world, along with many myriads of gods.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":206,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7f12c74e-7191-42d0-8d7f-a89ce8dcf714\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-14\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":99,\"uuid\":\"a3a439ab-23c3-4668-8b5b-c23d3151999c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the Sanskrit version the order is \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahā­maudgalyāyana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":55},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"08c2549e-ad1b-43d3-8d34-d4c43ae79953\",\"uuid\":\"3216a9e6-5240-4b2a-82c4-b0d41aa6a6d1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":57}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahākāśyapa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":68},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"b3b06ad4-5d91-4a74-aeb1-55b7caba1f9e\",\"uuid\":\"dc66dc8c-42ab-4130-8b88-fcccb92e987c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":68,\"end\":70}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahākapphiṇa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":82},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"aec33c7d-3cbe-4692-8aee-9f0d9f44b944\",\"uuid\":\"ec02e977-d363-4fee-97ac-c605af980476\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":82,\"end\":84}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahā­kātyāyana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":84,\"end\":98},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c712ec91-f592-400b-8c25-8be19053d214\",\"uuid\":\"8092ceb5-62cb-4742-8c10-3b972dea03a0\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":99}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"13f24c9b-b91d-4da9-88c2-806c6c19e313\",\"sort\":870,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.9\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Homage to all the buddhas and bodhisattvas. Thus did I hear at one time. The Bhagavān was dwelling in Śrāvastī, in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park, along with a large monastic saṅgha of 1,250 bhikṣus, all of them great elders, śrāvakas, and arhats, such as the elder Śāriputra, Mahā­maudgalyāyana, Mahākāśyapa, Mahā­kātyāyana, Mahākapphiṇa, Mahākauṣṭhila, Revata, Śuddhipaṃthaka, Nanda, Ānanda, Rāhula, Gavāṃpati, Bharadvāja, Kālodāyin, Vakula, and Aniruddha. He dwelt with these and other great śrāvakas and with many bodhisattva mahāsattvas, such as the youthful Mañjuśrī, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Ajita, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Gandhahastin, the bodhisattva mahāsattva Nityodyukta, and the bodhisattva mahāsattva Anikṣiptadhura, along with many other bodhisattva mahāsattvas. He was also accompanied by Śakra, the lord of gods, and Brahmā, the ruler of the Sahā world, along with many myriads of gods.\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"sort\":206,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"7f12c74e-7191-42d0-8d7f-a89ce8dcf714\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-14\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":181,\"uuid\":\"13f24c9b-b91d-4da9-88c2-806c6c19e313\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Literally, the text has “10 million (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bye ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":43},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":37,\"end\":43,\"uuid\":\"fe1bd5f6-df2f-41f1-add7-e73f0dcaf37e\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") x 10 billion (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":59}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"khrag khrig\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":70},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":59,\"end\":70,\"uuid\":\"79e47fc7-9c93-4e42-b315-1818c6fee0c7\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") x 100 thousand (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":70,\"end\":88}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’bum phrag\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":98},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":98,\"uuid\":\"59bdb3d7-b0f5-4559-9f77-f1d76274b8c1\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\").” In the Sanskrit it says, according to Max Müller, “a hundred thousand \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":98,\"end\":172}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nayutas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":179},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":172,\"end\":179,\"uuid\":\"cf447f35-e4f5-48dd-8105-aca0401b8258\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":179,\"end\":181}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"704dd861-194f-4dbb-9684-3093a5d6618e\",\"sort\":880,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.10\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Furthermore, Śāriputra, this bhagavān has an immeasurable saṅgha of śrāvakas, who are all pure arhats; their number cannot be easily expressed. Furthermore, Śāriputra, the sentient beings born in this buddha realm are all pure bodhisattvas who will not regress and are bound by only one more birth. Śāriputra, one cannot express the total number of bodhisattvas except to say that they are immeasurable or countless. Śāriputra, this buddha realm is beautifully adorned by such displays of the excellences of buddha realms.\",\"label\":\"1.9\",\"sort\":450,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"b63f60e8-a4d4-4dfa-8d22-6e147ac4ca78\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-22\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"704dd861-194f-4dbb-9684-3093a5d6618e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"These are \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":10}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bodhisattvas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":10,\"end\":22},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b\",\"uuid\":\"13d831e4-c387-448d-82d3-bf5fc20e7ef6\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" removed from enlightenment by only one more \u2028birth.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":74}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b3dfaa4f-50e0-4cdd-a1b4-21cc85d659e5\",\"sort\":884,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.11\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":157,\"uuid\":\"b3dfaa4f-50e0-4cdd-a1b4-21cc85d659e5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Skt. has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":13}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tāṃ pari­kīrtayāmi\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":31},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":13,\"end\":31,\"uuid\":\"17a50233-787b-4d0d-adcb-b37c5b95e108\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", “I praise this”; the feminine \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":63}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tāṃ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":66},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"4b7e9e61-c17f-4f96-9776-0c1fb5d534fa\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (missing, of course, in the Tibetan) shows that what is being praised is indeed \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":66,\"end\":147}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":147,\"end\":156},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"f9038fc4-c7aa-4c84-afc8-7530968acac5\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":156,\"end\":157}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f9f69d2-7674-434d-9390-b5d54d49c07f\",\"sort\":892,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.12\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48,\"uuid\":\"0f9f69d2-7674-434d-9390-b5d54d49c07f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This name is not mentioned in the Sanskrit text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":48}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"282c6b1b-9766-4a6f-b354-a92013a2347f\",\"sort\":894,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.13\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":69,\"uuid\":\"282c6b1b-9766-4a6f-b354-a92013a2347f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In the Sanskrit version this name is rendered as simply Meruprabhāsa.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":69}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"83ae4019-2090-40e2-b6f5-9a57594750d1\",\"sort\":896,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.14\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":210,\"uuid\":\"83ae4019-2090-40e2-b6f5-9a57594750d1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Tibetan version includes these last two names, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":51}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jam sgra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":60},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":51,\"end\":60,\"uuid\":\"90285f1b-778d-4ec4-97a5-26c90995df4f\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (*\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":63}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mañjuvacana\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":74},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":63,\"end\":74,\"uuid\":\"043295ea-5763-4957-9391-7f42e53fc14b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":74,\"end\":80}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’jam dbyangs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":80,\"end\":92},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":80,\"end\":92,\"uuid\":\"583acd34-2500-4e1a-99a9-f418b2cc24ad\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (*\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":92,\"end\":95}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mañjughoṣa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":95,\"end\":105},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":95,\"end\":105,\"uuid\":\"bfc692c9-0163-48b5-b72f-31342a22e678\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). There is no equivalent in the Sanskrit text, which instead has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":105,\"end\":171}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mañjudhvaja\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":171,\"end\":182},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c652489b-6d36-434b-89d4-db8cf895539e\",\"uuid\":\"6a39f926-f3e8-4ba6-8366-c080fc5d3868\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Beautiful Victory Banner).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":182,\"end\":210}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"9ac0a29d-a4b5-49bc-a9b5-0bfc1cc38217\",\"sort\":908,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.15\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96,\"uuid\":\"9ac0a29d-a4b5-49bc-a9b5-0bfc1cc38217\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Literally, the text says: “The buddhas cover their land with the power of their tongue faculty.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":96}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"d81665f2-3d46-4399-990d-130b094d69ae\",\"sort\":910,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.16\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“O Śāriputra, I, the Tathāgata, at present praise [this Sukhāvatī]. So, likewise, Śāriputra, in the east, the Tathāgata Akṣobhya, the Tathāgata Merudhvaja, the Tathāgata Meru, the Tathāgata Mahāmeru, the Tathāgata Mahā­meru­prabhāsa, the Tathāgata Harmonious Speech, the Tathāgata Harmonious Voice, and the other bhagavān buddhas of the east, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.12\",\"sort\":516,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"ddabdb92-ed2b-46d7-b65d-49d93737a6af\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-25\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":326,\"uuid\":\"d81665f2-3d46-4399-990d-130b094d69ae\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit text has \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":22}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sarva­buddha­pari­grahaṃ nāma dharma­paryāyam\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":67},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":67,\"uuid\":\"5dbbfb2f-fdd6-4941-86de-fc09aebfb378\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". This translates as, “You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called ‘The Grace [lit. the complete embrace] of All Buddhas.’ ” The word \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":67,\"end\":217}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"nāma\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":217,\"end\":221},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":217,\"end\":221,\"uuid\":\"eda4651f-3dbf-441f-9493-3279323b4f42\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (“called”) is missing in the Tibetan version, but has been added to clarify the meaning of this passage.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":221,\"end\":326}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e8300bb1-0eea-485d-8568-d4e8631cf5d6\",\"sort\":916,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.17\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the south, the bhagavān buddhas of the south, such as the Tathāgata Candra­sūrya­pradīpa, the Tathāgata Renown, the Tathāgata Yaśaḥprabha, the Tathāgata Mahārciskandha, the Tathāgata Merupradīpa, the Tathāgata Anaṃtavīrya, and others, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.13\",\"sort\":564,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3b95bbbf-9d29-4579-a7cb-3850adf92391\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-26\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47,\"uuid\":\"e8300bb1-0eea-485d-8568-d4e8631cf5d6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There is no equivalent in the Sanskrit version.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":47}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c1d34fe9-0783-46ec-bcbf-68cc2ef564f2\",\"sort\":918,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.18\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the west, the bhagavān buddhas of the west, such as the Tathāgata Amitāyus, the Tathāgata Amitaskandha, the Tathāgata Amitadhvaja, the Tathāgata Mahāprabha, the Tathāgata Illuminating Light Rays, the Tathāgata Ratnaketu, the Tathāgata Śuddha­raśmi­prabha, and others, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.14\",\"sort\":594,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"dfbc4c14-f7b2-4b68-a19c-2730d8f8dcce\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-27\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":65,\"uuid\":\"c1d34fe9-0783-46ec-bcbf-68cc2ef564f2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’od zer snang ba\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"a5526091-2807-4665-a7cf-104b36f94bdb\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". There is no equivalent in the Sanskrit version.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":65}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"bd2527e4-4533-4590-986c-4c3eb0ab42cf\",\"sort\":921,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.19\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the west, the bhagavān buddhas of the west, such as the Tathāgata Amitāyus, the Tathāgata Amitaskandha, the Tathāgata Amitadhvaja, the Tathāgata Mahāprabha, the Tathāgata Illuminating Light Rays, the Tathāgata Ratnaketu, the Tathāgata Śuddha­raśmi­prabha, and others, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.14\",\"sort\":594,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"dfbc4c14-f7b2-4b68-a19c-2730d8f8dcce\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-27\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41,\"uuid\":\"bd2527e4-4533-4590-986c-4c3eb0ab42cf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit version reads Mahāratnaketu.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f68f07b0-9fea-488c-9c93-6234353c6f8e\",\"sort\":923,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.20\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the north, the bhagavān buddhas of the north, such as the Tathāgata Mahārciskandha, the Tathāgata Vaiśvānara­nirghoṣa, the Tathāgata Duṣpradharṣa, the Tathāgata Āditya­saṃbhava, the Tathāgata Jālinīprabha, the Tathāgata Prabhākara, and others, who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.15\",\"sort\":628,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"6ad358df-a101-4264-b3de-2b75520ccccf\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-28\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":135,\"uuid\":\"f68f07b0-9fea-488c-9c93-6234353c6f8e\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit mentions another \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":30}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":39},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5\",\"uuid\":\"89151731-b47b-4d40-a838-2dd253a595af\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" who does not figure in the Tibetan, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":76}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":76,\"end\":85},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5\",\"uuid\":\"b434e758-8c3c-4ccb-8e56-a891fdfc1006\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":85,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Duṃdubhisvara­nirghoṣa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":108},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"d0f079d1-30f0-47be-8ac2-03bb80a06623\",\"uuid\":\"300d53a7-9cb4-4af1-99d8-fc97722d5202\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (=Dundubhisvara­nirghoṣa).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":108,\"end\":135}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"81d93ed2-8f29-4982-9580-e7bc73f53b69\",\"sort\":931,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.21\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the zenith, the bhagavān buddhas of the zenith, such as the Tathāgata Brahmaghoṣa, the Tathāgata Nakṣatrarāja, the Tathāgata Gandhottama, the Tathāgata Gandhaprabhāsa, the Tathāgata Heap of Incense, the Tathāgata Ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra, the Tathāgata Sālendrarāja, the Tathāgata Ratnotpalaśrī, the Tathāgata Sarvārthadarśa, the Tathāgata Sumerukalpa, and others who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises Sukhāvatī’s inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.17\",\"sort\":686,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3d624987-bc55-4790-a0b4-bc092b8cb188\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-30\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":80,\"uuid\":\"81d93ed2-8f29-4982-9580-e7bc73f53b69\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"spos kyi phung po\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17,\"uuid\":\"b6348a1e-312c-4436-bad2-05432df24172\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Sanskrit here reads \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":17,\"end\":43}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Mahārciskandha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":43,\"end\":57},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"a44dc3c6-c701-4dc0-95d9-7f38e1e9e5d1\",\"uuid\":\"9bb2f18d-af6b-46c6-b5f4-9bd140a506b4\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Great Mass of Light).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":80}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"ed61a5c3-0ff3-40e5-9fab-6f32e9e769a4\",\"sort\":936,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.22\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“Likewise, in the zenith, the bhagavān buddhas of the zenith, such as the Tathāgata Brahmaghoṣa, the Tathāgata Nakṣatrarāja, the Tathāgata Gandhottama, the Tathāgata Gandhaprabhāsa, the Tathāgata Heap of Incense, the Tathāgata Ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra, the Tathāgata Sālendrarāja, the Tathāgata Ratnotpalaśrī, the Tathāgata Sarvārthadarśa, the Tathāgata Sumerukalpa, and others who are as numerous as the grains of sand of the river Ganges, pervade their own buddha realms with the power of their speech and proclaim, ‘You should place your trust in this Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by all Buddhas,” which praises Sukhāvatī’s inconceivable qualities.’\",\"label\":\"1.17\",\"sort\":686,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"3d624987-bc55-4790-a0b4-bc092b8cb188\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-30\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":99,\"uuid\":\"ed61a5c3-0ff3-40e5-9fab-6f32e9e769a4\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit also mentions the \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":31}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Tathāgata\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":31,\"end\":40},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5\",\"uuid\":\"1191b157-c907-4238-8cb2-e0d16874f2ad\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" Indra­ketu­dhvaja­rāja, who is absent in the Tibetan text.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":40,\"end\":99}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b3bfbf3f-6d65-4dec-b2cc-2cda895dc2f6\",\"sort\":940,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.23\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"“What do you think about this, Śāriputra, why is this Dharma discourse called ‘Complete Embrace by All Buddhas’? Śāriputra, those sons and daughters of good family who have heard, now hear, or will hear this Dharma discourse and the names of those bhagavān buddhas will all be embraced completely by the bhagavān buddhas. Śāriputra, of all those sentient beings who aspire‍—who have made, are making, or will make aspirations‍—to the Sukhāvatī world, the buddha realm of the Bhagavān Tathāgata Amitābha, none has turned away, is turning away, or will ever turn away from the pursuit of unsurpassable, completely perfect enlightenment. Śāriputra, just as I now praise the inconceivable qualities of those bhagavān buddhas, likewise, Śāriputra, those bhagavān buddhas also praise my inconceivable qualities.”\",\"label\":\"1.18\",\"sort\":736,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"64ae5aa5-5b6b-4e18-927e-748b2f1aa01b\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-31\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":131,\"uuid\":\"b3bfbf3f-6d65-4dec-b2cc-2cda895dc2f6\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Sanskrit and Tibetan differ significantly here and in what immediately follows. We have translated on the basis of the Tibetan.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":131}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"daa1b4f9-8dd1-45e0-b31e-57045de35615\",\"sort\":942,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.24\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Śāriputra declared, “Bhagavān Śākyamuni, king of the Śākyas, you have fully awakened to unsurpassable, completely perfect enlightenment in this Sahā world. You have taught the Dharma that the whole world was reluctant to accept at the time of the degeneration of the eon, the degeneration of afflictions, the degeneration of beings, the degeneration of views, and the degeneration of lifespan. How marvelous indeed!”\",\"label\":\"1.19\",\"sort\":768,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9568d2bb-d47d-4bd4-92fc-44a7ce0b2e7a\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-32\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102,\"uuid\":\"daa1b4f9-8dd1-45e0-b31e-57045de35615\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here the Tibetan departs significantly from the Sanskrit, which has the other buddhas say these words.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":102}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5e48518e-b17f-496d-9e4e-dd8b3b758160\",\"sort\":944,\"type\":\"endnotes\",\"label\":\"n.25\",\"alignments\":{},\"references\":[{\"content\":\"Śāriputra declared, “Bhagavān Śākyamuni, king of the Śākyas, you have fully awakened to unsurpassable, completely perfect enlightenment in this Sahā world. You have taught the Dharma that the whole world was reluctant to accept at the time of the degeneration of the eon, the degeneration of afflictions, the degeneration of beings, the degeneration of views, and the degeneration of lifespan. How marvelous indeed!”\",\"label\":\"1.19\",\"sort\":768,\"type\":\"translation\",\"uuid\":\"9568d2bb-d47d-4bd4-92fc-44a7ce0b2e7a\",\"workUuid\":\"6b8535ee-2142-4007-afeb-bde05da84371\",\"xmlId\":\"UT22084-051-003-32\",\"toh\":null,\"alignments\":[],\"annotations\":[]}]},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":37,\"uuid\":\"5e48518e-b17f-496d-9e4e-dd8b3b758160\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":4}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"five degenerations\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":4,\"end\":22},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"c319c56a-27d7-4a3a-ac85-57e9b9b42b30\",\"uuid\":\"7aeb0d7d-730a-451b-99db-1e77735ec132\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". See glossary.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":22,\"end\":37}}]}]}],\"glossary\":[{\"uuid\":\"f0a03a9f-d197-4f62-889f-fd85bd047067\",\"authority\":\"018c8172-886d-43d5-9f97-74fa13d0cf3c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Āditya­saṃbhava\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉི་མའི་འབྱུང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"āditya­saṃbhava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyi ma’i ’byung\"}},{\"uuid\":\"582a1227-33ce-4cf9-9d02-ca6a279fa9c1\",\"authority\":\"4e175ef0-4e7d-4382-aae9-8655fb4d8253\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e. Not to be confused with \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003emgon po mi pham\u003c/em\u003e, Maitreya.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ajita\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་ཕམ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ajita\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi pham\"}},{\"uuid\":\"289fcb66-d5fb-47c3-8021-0a36cecfc88d\",\"authority\":\"cad43a0c-a53f-4f2e-8341-2a76e07dcb4a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eLit. “Not Disturbed” or “Immovable One.” The buddha in the eastern realm of Abhirati. A well-known buddha in Mahāyāna, regarded in the higher tantras as the head of one of the five buddha families, the vajra family in the east.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Akṣobhya\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་འཁྲུགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"akṣobhya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi ’khrugs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"authority\":\"52456ea4-51a5-46fa-8f83-56abbc67c5c4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eBuddha associated with \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-170\\\"\u003eSukhāvatī\u003c/span\u003e; buddha of the western direction; principal buddha of the Pure Land tradition; as the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e Dharmākara, he made forty-eight original vows (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epraṇidhāna\u003c/em\u003e) to bring beings to enlightenment, thus establishing \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-170\\\"\u003eSukhāvatī\u003c/span\u003e for their benefit; in tantrism he is one of the five dhyāni-buddhas and is associated with the aggregate of notions (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003esaṃjñā­skandha\u003c/em\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitābha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitābha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2035d5ec-b30a-4ca2-b0ae-0868fb827fcd\",\"authority\":\"bb7f9839-9f93-458a-8662-6cadc2653e8e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitadhvaja\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་མསཐན་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitadhvaja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal msthan dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5539c34a-3c5f-4958-a1f3-03d9ac386042\",\"authority\":\"3876102b-1249-41bf-9178-622e5b6a3db0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitaskandha\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕུང་པོ་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitaskandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phung po dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"016abcba-d2ad-4141-a0c4-a1630608c46a\",\"authority\":\"46d135e0-0d59-43cd-9955-45a1d1cbb6d8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eBuddha especially associated with life energy and long life; the sambhogakāya aspect of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-97\\\"\u003eAmitābha\u003c/span\u003e. Also a name of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-97\\\"\u003eAmitābha\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Amitāyus\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚེ་དཔག་མེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"amitāyus\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshe dpag med\"}},{\"uuid\":\"bec64dc6-b515-4d47-9b60-1709b8279767\",\"authority\":\"641ec093-394e-4440-a36c-439debdcffa4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anaṃtavīrya\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྩོན་འགྲུས་མཐའ་ཡས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anaṃtavīrya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtson ’grus mtha’ yas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0446e177-94b7-4a9e-b711-96fcb9641820\",\"authority\":\"2c02baf4-0ece-4579-8f66-c49bcc21f21f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA major śrāvaka disciple and personal attendant of the Buddha Śākyamuni during the last twenty-five years of his life. He was a cousin of the Buddha (according to the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eMahāvastu\u003c/cite\u003e, he was a son of Śuklodana, one of the brothers of King Śuddhodana, which means he was a brother of Devadatta; other sources say he was a son of Amṛtodana, another brother of King Śuddhodana, which means he would have been a brother of Aniruddha).\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eĀnanda, having always been in the Buddha’s presence, is said to have memorized all the teachings he heard and is celebrated for having recited all the Buddha’s teachings by memory at the first council of the Buddhist saṅgha, thus preserving the teachings after the Buddha’s parinirvāṇa. The phrase “Thus did I hear at one time,” found at the beginning of the sūtras, usually stands for his recitation of the teachings. He became a patriarch after the passing of Mahākāśyapa.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ānanda\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀུན་དགའ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ānanda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kun dga’ bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"fd580cc8-2f2e-4ccc-918e-6d2c9f814259\",\"authority\":\"7f5c1186-ed32-4b9c-b588-467f1b504255\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Anikṣiptadhura\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྩོན་པའི་མི་འདོར།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anikṣiptadhura\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brtson pa’i mi ’dor\"}},{\"uuid\":\"599e0a5f-bd97-4b1d-a66d-deaf0cc92f50\",\"authority\":\"dd800f86-676c-4b72-b850-913c527051b9\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Aniruddha\",\"tibetan\":\"མ་འགག་པ།, འགགས་པ་མེད་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aniruddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ma ’gag pa, ’gags pa med pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"69c51647-a349-4599-ae95-dbde5c407416\",\"authority\":\"d95e6f28-87de-429e-b185-d12873ac760c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eAccording to Buddhist tradition, one who is worthy of worship (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003epūjām arhati\u003c/em\u003e), or one who has conquered the enemies, the mental afflictions (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ekleśa-ari-hata-vat\u003c/em\u003e), and reached liberation from the cycle of rebirth and suffering. It is the fourth and highest of the four fruits attainable by śrāvakas. Also used as an epithet of the Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"arhat\",\"tibetan\":\"དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"arhat\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dgra bcom pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2b04d627-b147-4363-9cc0-bf9ae96a744e\",\"authority\":\"07a6a5e2-c605-4a1c-b229-1a5b37f71417\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eYeshé Dé (late eighth to early ninth century) was the most prolific translator of sūtras into Tibetan. Altogether he is credited with the translation of more than one hundred sixty sūtra translations and more than one hundred additional translations, mostly on tantric topics. In spite of Yeshé Dé’s great importance for the propagation of Buddhism in Tibet during the imperial era, only a few biographical details about this figure are known. Later sources describe him as a student of the Indian teacher Padmasambhava, and he is also credited with teaching both sūtra and tantra widely to students of his own. He was also known as Nanam Yeshé Dé, from the Nanam (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003esna nam\u003c/em\u003e) clan.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bandé Yeshé Dé\",\"tibetan\":\"བན་དེ་ཡེ་ཤེས་སྡེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ban de ye shes sde\"}},{\"uuid\":\"352fd1e2-6817-483a-8dc6-2a68cc2cc7dd\",\"authority\":\"6e7d97ae-2219-4971-8336-362aa5cfc678\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003ePrecious/semiprecious stone; sometimes translated as lapis lazuli.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"beryl\",\"tibetan\":\"བཻ་དཱུ་རྱ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiḍūrya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bai dU rya\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ac3d1322-40ec-43b9-a027-cf2bbc3eac29\",\"authority\":\"2b190410-5ef2-4a3a-a428-89d999d14336\",\"definition\":\"$20\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bhagavān\",\"tibetan\":\"བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bhagavat, bhagavān\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bcom ldan ’das\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0100018f-0b4e-41c5-8907-42c281cb5be4\",\"authority\":\"026210ea-b560-4ffb-b6f1-4c8374157a39\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e; one of the sixteen sthavira \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e (see “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-52\\\"\u003eelder\u003c/span\u003e”).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Bharadvāja\",\"tibetan\":\"བྷ་ར་དྷབ༹་ཛ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bharadvāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bha ra dh+va dza\"}},{\"uuid\":\"12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b\",\"authority\":\"0254f753-e084-4cdc-9ac3-184aaad94610\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA being who is dedicated to the cultivation and fulfilment of the altruistic intention to attain perfect buddhahood, traversing the ten bodhisattva levels (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003edaśabhūmi\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003esa bcu\u003c/em\u003e). Bodhisattvas purposely opt to remain within cyclic existence in order to liberate all sentient beings, instead of simply seeking personal freedom from suffering. In terms of the view, they realize both the selflessness of persons and the selflessness of phenomena.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"bodhisattva\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhi­sattva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub sems dpa’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e9de2fe9-8140-41b9-89a0-010b6ef93ce6\",\"authority\":\"db36127a-581c-4efe-9ebf-172706c136f8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLord of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-144\\\"\u003eSahā world\u003c/span\u003e (q.v.). Buddhists see \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e as a god occupying a high position in cyclic existence, with a very long life and a great deal of power.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmā\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmā\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"337b83f8-04a2-4de9-b0d6-df74d2ba2e15\",\"authority\":\"feb54dc5-6f8d-4272-84ff-aed68c69e065\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Brahmaghoṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཚངས་པའི་དབྱངས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"brahmaghoṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"tshangs pa’i dbyangs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6c29513e-d408-4dce-bf30-bb680944251e\",\"authority\":\"ca63bb7f-ceba-45f1-b520-ac2199b60741\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe branches of (1) authentic mindfulness, (2) authentic discrimination of dharmas, (3) authentic perseverance, (4) authentic joy, (5) authentic serenity, (6) authentic meditative absorption, and (7) authentic equanimity.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"branches of enlightenment\",\"tibetan\":\"བྱང་ཆུབ་ཀྱི་ཡན་ལག\",\"sanskrit\":\"bodhyaṅgāni\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"byang chub kyi yan lag\"}},{\"uuid\":\"300caeec-47cd-4381-9bf3-e0e64e410772\",\"authority\":\"c9f0857b-d857-482a-9418-c26dd33b12a8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Candra­sūrya­pradīpa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉི་ཟླ་སྒྲོན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"candra­sūrya­pradīpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyi zla sgron ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6e956151-b3eb-4769-a347-3f7728356ae4\",\"authority\":\"d40eaf0e-5fdb-47a7-8ae9-e10103db5de9\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"coral\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤུག་གི་ཤིང་།\",\"sanskrit\":\"musāragalva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spug gi shing\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6ea36a2d-dfe5-4a59-89e6-122a54ef1e91\",\"authority\":\"64b1beaa-3959-4336-b0ca-77692e73effd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e, one of the sixteen sthavira \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e (see “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-52\\\"\u003eelder\u003c/span\u003e”).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Cūḍapanthaka\",\"tibetan\":\"ལམ་ཕྲན་བསྟན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"cūḍapanthaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lam phran bstan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cc129426-225c-49dd-9d7d-d38b5291a7bb\",\"authority\":\"c768392b-e762-4e7e-b4ac-4d59c7bd7632\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eTranslator of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eSukhāvatī­vyūha­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dānaśīla\",\"tibetan\":\"དཱ་ན་ཤཱི་ལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dānaśīla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dA na shI la\"}},{\"uuid\":\"4e9e0ffb-e9a8-43e5-b5d5-bea9bd8f9630\",\"authority\":\"1ed0043d-7088-427a-8d5e-e3d88b302b04\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmadhara\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་འཛིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos ’dzin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"442d4241-cda7-4bee-9120-0455941a9901\",\"authority\":\"6386e1c7-2ccd-4ff1-a655-d3f1ca46d4fb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Dharmadhvaja\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྒྱལ་མཚན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharmadhvaja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos kyi rgyal mtshan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d0f079d1-30f0-47be-8ac2-03bb80a06623\",\"authority\":\"5a20e253-6dad-43ad-b152-45dbb07b2284\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Duṃdubhisvara­nirghoṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"duṃdubhisvara­nirghoṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5784850c-540a-4a57-933a-5684a7764ec2\",\"authority\":\"6722d085-6a17-4830-8188-452df8c6540d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Duṣpradharṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"རབ་ཏུ་ཐུལ་དཀའ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"duṣpradharṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rab tu thul dka’\"}},{\"uuid\":\"44d992ce-75e8-4352-894d-0a1badff5874\",\"authority\":\"0be6f101-6cf9-46b0-ae61-673caab6dc58\",\"definition\":\"$21\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"elder\",\"tibetan\":\"གནས་བརྟན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sthavira\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gnas brtan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"199e0291-ee9c-427a-8e31-6e47ef322b42\",\"authority\":\"cd5f0882-8589-48b3-aa20-917e503cda88\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"emerald\",\"tibetan\":\"རྡོའི་སྙིང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"aśmagarbha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rdo’i snying po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c319c56a-27d7-4a3a-ac85-57e9b9b42b30\",\"authority\":\"16634033-bb38-49c5-9048-21ff9b967e91\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003efive degenerations\u003c/span\u003e are (1) the degeneration of life span, (2) the degeneration of views, (3) the degeneration of the afflictions, (4) the degeneration of beings, and (5) the degeneration of the era.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"five degenerations\",\"tibetan\":\"སྙིགས་མ་ལྔ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"pañcakaṣāya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"snyigs ma lnga\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0fcc400e-0eb1-4dba-9bb0-2dc2eca1ef35\",\"authority\":\"7139ec2b-b215-4475-b693-0591be334183\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA person who has manifested the complete enlightenment of a buddha of the Greater Vehicle.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"fully awakened\",\"tibetan\":\"མངོན་པར་རྫོགས་པར་སངས་རྒྱས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"abhisaṃbuddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mngon par rdzogs par sangs rgyas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"7bd94653-51b8-490d-abe2-7858e6e9042f\",\"authority\":\"f26b2d87-6789-4d54-be2e-f0a6378b96a0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gandhahastin\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོས་ཀྱི་གླང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandhahastin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spos kyi glang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"be55b2b6-ff5f-4ffe-ba61-68e70f3cad76\",\"authority\":\"70e0b9c3-94b3-4392-a2f8-9e1b6ee49847\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gandhaprabhāsa\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོས་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandhaprabhāsa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spos ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a91dd7af-e500-43dc-a760-ae1cf5fc09be\",\"authority\":\"74461fd0-5ed8-4923-b6bb-16bb40dfa426\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eA class of generally benevolent nonhuman beings who inhabit the skies, sometimes said to inhabit fantastic cities in the clouds, and more specifically to dwell on the eastern slopes of Mount Meru, where they are ruled by the Great King Dhṛtarāṣṭra. They are most renowned as celestial musicians who serve the gods. In the Abhidharma, the term is also used to refer to the mental body assumed by sentient beings during the intermediate state between death and rebirth. Gandharvas are said to live on fragrances (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003egandha\u003c/em\u003e) in the desire realm, hence the Tibetan translation \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003edri za\u003c/em\u003e, meaning “scent eater.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"gandharva\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲི་ཟ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandharva\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dri za\"}},{\"uuid\":\"2bdd0277-a2ca-4881-a150-052e5313a29e\",\"authority\":\"6f71a7bb-be99-447f-ab8a-4162d6ec6d6f\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gandhottama\",\"tibetan\":\"སྤོས་མཆོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"gandhottama\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"spos mchog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"efcf655a-f029-473a-981e-65188b267821\",\"authority\":\"edf51f56-abfc-43ff-81a0-d2ef57306e0e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e; one of the Buddha’s five close \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e disciples. He took ordination from the Buddha and then became a disciple of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-74\\\"\u003eŚāriputra\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Gavāṃpati\",\"tibetan\":\"བ་ལང་བདག\",\"sanskrit\":\"gavāṃpati\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ba lang bdag\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a4978597-e1f4-4673-bddf-53b064a56656\",\"authority\":\"bf90de60-0724-4f71-94ae-05831f69adcc\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Jālinīprabha\",\"tibetan\":\"དྲ་བ་ཅན་གྱི་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jālenīprabha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dra ba can gyi ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3f9da289-6926-4284-8fc0-c88a5c8710b8\",\"authority\":\"86c17e77-82a6-4b77-bd21-3f012d36f1f5\",\"definition\":\"$22\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Jeta’s Grove, Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park\",\"tibetan\":\"རྒྱལ་བུ་རྒྱལ་བྱེད་ཀྱི་ཚལ་མགོན་མེད་ཟས་སྦྱིན་གྱི་ཀུན་དགའ་ར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"jetavanam anāthapiṇḍadasyārāmaḥ\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rgyal bu rgyal byed kyi tshal mgon med zas sbyin gyi kun dga’ ra ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cc0bc8b5-a812-4464-9f51-013a41def137\",\"authority\":\"948ceb6a-e405-418f-9959-9c78f8d9a73c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Kālodāyin\",\"tibetan\":\"འཆར་བྱེད་ནག་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"kālodāyin\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’char byed nag po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"71de5a26-899a-49b1-af00-bf2dd62d6a9e\",\"authority\":\"da44adf0-9a05-47f8-aebf-0a5485d7dbea\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eLord of Death.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Lord of Death\",\"tibetan\":\"གཤིན་རྗེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yama\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gshin rje\"}},{\"uuid\":\"aec33c7d-3cbe-4692-8aee-9f0d9f44b944\",\"authority\":\"4943158d-bfeb-4e7e-bfc4-6950224d65d8\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahākapphiṇa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀ་པི་ན་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahākapphiṇa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ka pi na chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b3b06ad4-5d91-4a74-aeb1-55b7caba1f9e\",\"authority\":\"1aff34d4-5da6-49ab-b312-523fffccb2d7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e, one of the most important followers of the Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahākāśyapa\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་སྲུང་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahākāśyapa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od srung chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c712ec91-f592-400b-8c25-8be19053d214\",\"authority\":\"0bdb7926-aba8-4e98-8a0f-dd172e756ce7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahā­kātyāyana\",\"tibetan\":\"ཀཱ་ཏྱཱའི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­kātyāyana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"kA tyA’i bu chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0bc0e51f-934d-4dea-821a-be5424257020\",\"authority\":\"3adac520-7720-4880-ae09-5461382ab20e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahākauṣṭhila\",\"tibetan\":\"གསུས་པོ་ཆེ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahākauṣṭhila\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"gsus po che\"}},{\"uuid\":\"08c2549e-ad1b-43d3-8d34-d4c43ae79953\",\"authority\":\"33bf04de-6482-4680-bbee-b6410380d8e6\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e, one of the most important followers of the Buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahā­maudgalyāyana\",\"tibetan\":\"མཽད་གལ་གྱི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­maudgalyāyana\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"maud gal gyi bu chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c44d3b6a-16ca-4e2f-b5b2-72b27d50179f\",\"authority\":\"50efa3cd-d428-43fa-a637-2aca2db98db5\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahāmeru\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷུན་པོ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahāmeru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhun po chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"668ec6ff-23f8-448a-a18e-670b1380e40c\",\"authority\":\"2d178430-e493-4aac-ab3c-9684d010c554\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahā­meru­prabhāsa\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷུན་པོ་ཆེན་པོ་སྣང་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahā­meru­prabhāsa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhun po chen po snang ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"efbce404-5ab0-4fa7-a273-a680ddb28630\",\"authority\":\"5b5e6be3-cef9-4014-b2bd-1502a8d2579c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahāprabha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་ཆེན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahāprabha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od chen\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a44dc3c6-c701-4dc0-95d9-7f38e1e9e5d1\",\"authority\":\"8425bce5-3019-48f4-a56b-9f54a553cc43\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mahārciskandha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་འཕྲོའི་ཕུང་པོ་ཆེན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mahārciskandha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od ’phro’i phung po chen po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3467117e-28dd-43da-86cb-596f3d7434dc\",\"authority\":\"54e7495d-44dc-464f-b9dd-ea59649da018\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eOne of the five trees of Indra’s paradise, its heavenly flowers often rain down in salutation of the buddhas and bodhisattvas and are said to be very bright and aromatic, gladdening the hearts of those who see them. In our world, it is a tree native to India, \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eErythrina indica\u003c/em\u003e or \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eErythrina variegata\u003c/em\u003e, commonly known as the Indian coral tree, mandarava tree, flame tree, and tiger’s claw. In the early spring, before its leaves grow, the tree is fully covered in large flowers, which are rich in nectar and attract many birds. Although the most widespread coral tree has red crimson flowers, the color of the blossoms is not usually mentioned in the sūtras themselves, and it may refer to some other kinds, like the rarer \u003cem class=\\\"foreign\\\"\u003eErythrina indica alba\u003c/em\u003e, which boasts white flowers.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"mandārava\",\"tibetan\":\"མན་དཱ་ར་བ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mandārava\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"man dA ra ba\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c652489b-6d36-434b-89d4-db8cf895539e\",\"authority\":\"e911016e-3480-4af5-864e-15d5ad1a683e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mañjudhvaja\",\"tibetan\":\"\",\"sanskrit\":\"mañjudhvaja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"\"}},{\"uuid\":\"30bbcb97-b2e0-49a3-90f9-d92930f4a899\",\"authority\":\"320c5523-4cde-4365-aeb1-3e69be9b0e42\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eMañjuśrī is one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha” and a bodhisattva who embodies wisdom. He is a major figure in the Mahāyāna sūtras, appearing often as an interlocutor of the Buddha. In his most well-known iconographic form, he is portrayed bearing the sword of wisdom in his right hand and a volume of the \u003ccite class=\\\"title break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003ePrajñā­pāramitā­sūtra\u003c/cite\u003e in his left. To his name, Mañjuśrī, meaning “Gentle and Glorious One,” is often added the epithet Kumārabhūta, “having a youthful form.” He is also called Mañjughoṣa, Mañjusvara, and Pañcaśikha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Mañjuśrī\",\"tibetan\":\"འཇམ་དཔལ་གཞོན་ནུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"mañjuśrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’jam dpal gzhon nu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"50ea35ec-22af-401a-8781-677dae8da4b2\",\"authority\":\"4d726e80-5ae2-4fd7-b13c-6017bd6bf388\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Meru\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷུན་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"meru\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhun po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e9937693-da05-4201-ab76-086c56101a86\",\"authority\":\"103d59a5-c981-4e77-ae54-3d3e1aab788e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Merudhvaja\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷུན་པོ་རྒྱལ་མཚན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"merudhvaja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhun po rgyal mtshan\"}},{\"uuid\":\"785b6780-ca7f-4127-96b4-322f31755f8c\",\"authority\":\"b380aa97-674c-4b16-a59f-875e83167309\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Merupradīpa\",\"tibetan\":\"ལྷུན་པོའི་སྒྲོན་མ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"merupradīpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"lhun po’i sgron ma\"}},{\"uuid\":\"963ca73b-4128-4973-9074-fb96471f50e8\",\"authority\":\"3eb5ab69-978a-400b-8ad1-7c5ad9755286\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Nakṣatrarāja\",\"tibetan\":\"སྐར་མའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nakṣatrarāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"skar m’i rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6ec612e0-8c00-4d85-ba39-15ee82bb32e2\",\"authority\":\"5f5d193a-f8c5-48ea-9cb9-1ef7e5f550bd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Nanda\",\"tibetan\":\"དགའ་བོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nanda\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dga’ bo\"}},{\"uuid\":\"ef9e56ec-eb73-48fc-ada9-69370cc7a2fa\",\"authority\":\"2a3871e4-e448-45db-b811-80087391eb5d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Nityodyukta\",\"tibetan\":\"རྟག་ཏུ་བཙོན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"nityodyukta\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rtag tu btson\"}},{\"uuid\":\"e4055571-7f0c-4b3e-b35e-962919a4230d\",\"authority\":\"67fec56e-ef33-4f73-9011-b0d52844a0ed\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA stage on the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattva\u003c/span\u003e path where the practitioner will never turn back, or be turned back, from progress toward the full awakening of a buddha.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"not regress\",\"tibetan\":\"ཕྱིར་མི་ལྡོག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"phyir mi ldog pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"dc33eabf-781b-46a7-b33f-222eda12328a\",\"authority\":\"e2d497a3-8798-47f3-95ea-ddacc906a379\",\"definition\":\"\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"palm tree\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤིང་ཏ་ལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tāla\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shing ta la\"}},{\"uuid\":\"053d45ba-7799-42ef-9329-e5de8f15985f\",\"authority\":\"9fdd9aab-c544-4a22-bde1-502c5f644ddb\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eA term used to emphasize the superiority of buddhahood when contrasted with the achievement of the \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e and pratyekabuddhas. A samyaksaṃbuddha is considered superior by virtue of his compassionate activity, his omniscience, and his ten special \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-63\\\"\u003epowers\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"perfectly and fully enlightened buddha\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡང་དག་པར་རྫོགས་པའི་སངས་རྒྱས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"samyaksaṃbuddha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yang dag par rdzogs pa’i sangs rgyas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"51f52255-edd6-4293-bc12-e2cf1728c67b\",\"authority\":\"07bf1655-7a5b-48dd-a6bd-431b610812c4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe five powers, or faculties, are those of (1) faith, (2) perseverence, (3) mindfulness, (4) meditative absorption or samādhi, and (5) wisdom or prajñā.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"powers\",\"tibetan\":\"དབང་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"indriya\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"dbang po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"cbf396c1-57a6-4983-8aef-940ca730e637\",\"authority\":\"b78449c3-2213-4cd2-92d2-aa8066d1ab16\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Prabhākara\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་ཀྱི་བྱུང་གནས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"prabhākara\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od kyi byung gnas\"}},{\"uuid\":\"3ba91505-bc0f-4713-a614-61ffedacfce0\",\"authority\":\"a05175c9-e2b3-438b-bfb4-4670ca3ddf37\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e, one of the sixteen sthavira \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e (see “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-52\\\"\u003eelder\u003c/span\u003e”).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Rāhula\",\"tibetan\":\"སྒྲ་གཅན་ཟིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"rāhula\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sgra gcan zin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"917c67f3-965c-4e0c-aa13-bf57faab3698\",\"authority\":\"5fcc3546-940e-4b9c-bd12-77b1f0e49dfd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ratnaketu\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་ཏོག\",\"sanskrit\":\"ratnaketu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin po che’i tog\"}},{\"uuid\":\"63a0e2a5-2f58-4cad-8c46-d472a0c8381a\",\"authority\":\"14981091-2975-4dae-baa1-09f0a3013a6c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་ཆེན་མེ་ཏོག་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྒྱས་པའི་རིགས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin chen me tog shin tu rgyas pa’i rigs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"b3be1416-815c-464a-a552-1f8f5a577795\",\"authority\":\"a9b9f355-b4d9-44f4-8c74-4ebde94fb155\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Ratnotpalaśrī\",\"tibetan\":\"རིན་ཆེན་ཨུད་པ་ལའི་དཔལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"ratnotpalaśrī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"rin chen ud pa la’i dpal\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d7eab3d7-6add-4eff-b3b9-d30ececf3242\",\"authority\":\"e385a5c7-08a7-4b5e-9ac7-d1a559e93ead\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Revata\",\"tibetan\":\"ནམ་གྲུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"revata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nam gru\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5d788529-5cfd-445d-a109-2c736276ff68\",\"authority\":\"53c4843a-47d4-4c6c-9809-8e95f5045eb3\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThis universe of ours, presided over by \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-96\\\"\u003eBrahmā\u003c/span\u003e. The term is variously interpreted as meaning the world of suffering, of endurance, of fearlessness, or of concomitance (of karmic cause and effect).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sahā world\",\"tibetan\":\"མི་མཇེད་ཀྱི་འཇིག་རྟེན།, མི་མཇེད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sahā, sahā­loka­dhatu\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mi mjed, mi mjed kyi ’jig rten\"}},{\"uuid\":\"1345f24e-bf84-468e-b250-5a1fec39c3d9\",\"authority\":\"6fbdb5b0-3b2a-4d90-a1e1-76b9a42657e0\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eThe lord of the gods in the Heaven of the Thirty-Three (\u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003etrāyastriṃśa\u003c/em\u003e). Alternatively known as Indra, the deity that is called “lord of the gods” dwells on the summit of Mount Sumeru and wields the thunderbolt. The Tibetan translation \u003cem class=\\\"foreign text-wy\\\" lang=\\\"bo-LATN\\\"\u003ebrgya byin\u003c/em\u003e (meaning “one hundred sacrifices”) is based on an etymology that \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśakra\u003c/em\u003e is an abbreviation of \u003cem class=\\\"foreign break text-sa\\\" lang=\\\"sa-LATN\\\"\u003eśata-kratu\u003c/em\u003e, one who has performed a hundred sacrifices. Each world with a central Sumeru has a Śakra. Also known by other names such as Kauśika, Devendra, and Śacipati. \u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śakra\",\"tibetan\":\"བརྒྱ་བྱིན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śakra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"brgya byin\"}},{\"uuid\":\"d06e0aac-8497-4476-acb3-e2aa986048fa\",\"authority\":\"1a5439d5-16d3-4759-98b5-8b84dafbbd3e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sālendrarāja\",\"tibetan\":\"སཱ་ལའི་དབང་པོའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sālendrarāja\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"sA la’i dbang po’i rgyal po\"}},{\"uuid\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"authority\":\"028f92a7-eb1f-4d2a-9d19-a4c4c188481c\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eOne of the principal śrāvaka disciples of the Buddha, he was renowned for his discipline and for having been praised by the Buddha as foremost of the wise (often paired with Maudgalyā­yana, who was praised as foremost in the capacity for miraculous powers). His father, Tiṣya, to honor Śāriputra’s mother, Śārikā, named him Śāradvatīputra, or, in its contracted form, Śāriputra, meaning “Śārikā’s Son.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śāriputra\",\"tibetan\":\"ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śāriputra\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"shA ri’i bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"0ee143cc-6dde-417f-bcd6-5a42b7216b18\",\"authority\":\"596143e2-1cdc-426a-a95a-8371349d6016\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sarvārthadarśa\",\"tibetan\":\"མཐོང་བ་དོན་ཡོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sarvārthadarśa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mthong ba don yod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"babb1949-536c-4429-8401-6734edce8fe4\",\"authority\":\"56ad8b12-01d1-40be-8ede-a545d856aaf2\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Siṃha\",\"tibetan\":\"སེང་གེ\",\"sanskrit\":\"siṃha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"seng ge\"}},{\"uuid\":\"a228dd64-edf0-47f9-8d90-55883408ec6a\",\"authority\":\"b662e79b-4cff-4567-b74a-1c23d3f1fea7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eHīnayāna practitioner of the first turning of the wheel of the Dharma on the four noble truths, who realizes the suffering inherent in saṃsāra and focuses on understanding that there is no independent self. By conquering disturbing emotions, he liberates himself, attaining first the stage of stream enterer at the path of seeing, followed by the stage of once-returner who will be reborn only one more time, and then the stage of non-returner who will no longer be reborn into saṃsāra. The final goal is to become an \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e. These four stages are also known as the “four results of spiritual practice.”\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"śrāvaka\",\"tibetan\":\"ཉན་ཐོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrāvaka\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"nyan thos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"61aa044f-aaea-4d30-b1ae-efbd23d8aaa4\",\"authority\":\"55532312-84c3-4ab9-9220-58b7598c8440\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp\u003eDuring the life of the Buddha, Śrāvastī was the capital city of the powerful kingdom of Kośala, ruled by King Prasenajit, who became a follower and patron of the Buddha. It was also the hometown of Anāthapiṇḍada, the wealthy patron who first invited the Buddha there, and then offered him a park known as Jetavana, Prince Jeta’s Grove, which became one of the first Buddhist monasteries. The Buddha is said to have spent about twenty-five rainy seasons with his disciples in Śrāvastī, thus it is named as the setting of numerous events and teachings. It is located in present-day Uttar Pradesh in northern India.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śrāvastī\",\"tibetan\":\"མཉན་ཡོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śrāvastī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"mnyan yod\"}},{\"uuid\":\"f50cfb2f-a0d3-4937-abc7-32f85ec32a25\",\"authority\":\"0c5ec4ad-cb20-4880-bf35-62ca54d81186\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eFor the five \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003estrengths\u003c/span\u003e, see “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-63\\\"\u003epowers\u003c/span\u003e.” The ten \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003estrengths\u003c/span\u003e can refer either to one set of ten qualities of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgatas\u003c/span\u003e, or to a different list of ten \u003cspan class=\\\"ignore\\\"\u003estrengths\u003c/span\u003e of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-55\\\"\u003ebodhisattvas\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"strengths\",\"tibetan\":\"སྟོབས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bala\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"stobs\"}},{\"uuid\":\"eb18fa0e-9f40-4ab1-87f5-8835b07d99a7\",\"authority\":\"59aa4032-aeae-4ba3-a213-45c99dd9db6e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Śuddha­raśmi­prabha\",\"tibetan\":\"འོད་ཟེར་དག་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"śuddha­raśmi­prabha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"’od zer dag pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"authority\":\"d90b157d-b522-4df3-8bb3-0e2b4938a3fd\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eMeaning “the delightful” or “the land of delight,” the name of the buddhafield of \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-97\\\"\u003eAmitābha\u003c/span\u003e / \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-98\\\"\u003eAmitāyus\u003c/span\u003e, in the western direction from our world.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"tibetan\":\"བདེ་བ་ཅན།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sukhāvatī\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bde ba can\"}},{\"uuid\":\"55dd1b30-2b7f-484f-8b2a-f54eb9c8ad6a\",\"authority\":\"b59ca3d2-b428-450a-bc04-d4953d53b178\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Sumerukalpa\",\"tibetan\":\"རི་རབ་ལྟ་བུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"sumerukalpa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ri rab lta bu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5\",\"authority\":\"285a8525-75c9-4ab3-8d61-e257c5eb21ce\",\"definition\":\"$23\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"tathāgata\",\"tibetan\":\"དེ་བཞིན་གཤེགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"tathāgata\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"de bzhin gshegs pa\"}},{\"uuid\":\"189fde85-23ea-4ae0-8633-ec042c2d08db\",\"authority\":\"f078da83-ec7e-438f-ba01-f30e8d6d1f9a\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Tathāgata Dharma\",\"tibetan\":\"ཆོས།\",\"sanskrit\":\"dharma\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"chos\"}},{\"uuid\":\"19c87c79-3035-4fbc-b20a-8c66a6846f26\",\"authority\":\"f1d0fcd8-787c-4609-9ffc-f590417f6099\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eAn enlightenment that is authentically complete.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"unsurpassable, completely perfect enlightenment\",\"tibetan\":\"བླ་ན་མེད་པ་ཡང་དག་པར་རྫོགས་པའི་བྱང་ཆུབ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"anuttara­samyak­saṃbodhi\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"bla na med pa yang dag par rdzogs pa’i byang chub\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5d519b6d-47d9-4cd5-9360-8858e776cd28\",\"authority\":\"7b76ec0a-9ba6-4490-b77e-2c5c6d0cdc8e\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vaiśvānara­nirghoṣa\",\"tibetan\":\"ཐམས་ཅད་སྒྲོལ་བའི་དབྱངས་སྒྲོལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"vaiśvānara­nirghoṣa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"thams cad sgrol ba’i dbyangs sgrol\"}},{\"uuid\":\"6c8e57e3-13aa-49fd-9c28-46ccb755085f\",\"authority\":\"116b2283-ccf6-45ef-afb2-af307dec56d7\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003e\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-53\\\"\u003eŚrāvaka\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhat\u003c/span\u003e; one of the sixteen sthavira \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-54\\\"\u003earhats\u003c/span\u003e (see “\u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-52\\\"\u003eelder\u003c/span\u003e”).\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Vakula\",\"tibetan\":\"བ་ཀུ་ལ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"bakula\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"ba ku la\"}},{\"uuid\":\"5dca12bb-41c2-4344-b250-004caab85340\",\"authority\":\"371f187c-40ee-46cb-882d-fd96d141e892\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eThe eight qualities of water: (1) sweet-tasting; (2) cool; (3) soft; (4) light; (5) transparent; (6) clean; (7) not harmful to the throat; and (8) beneficial to the stomach.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"water possessing the eight qualities\",\"tibetan\":\"ཡན་ལག་བརྒྱད་དང་ལྡན་པའི་ཆུ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"yan lag brgyad dang ldan pa’i chu\"}},{\"uuid\":\"8d5a2c19-5565-4b33-8401-8b7a666b93c2\",\"authority\":\"07109fb2-456d-40a5-8c60-a118fcce869d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yaśaḥprabha\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲགས་པའི་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yaśaḥprabha\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grags pa’i ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"34c79710-b026-450f-82c9-1d14d9f55f56\",\"authority\":\"3afd41de-4c8f-4608-b855-b93081a6647d\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yaśaḥprabhāsa\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲགས་འོད།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yaśaḥprabhāsa\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grags ’od\"}},{\"uuid\":\"c0a5489f-9a0b-40ae-8922-9cb9dae9f0db\",\"authority\":\"870db968-3cd3-4c22-9c52-6c3caf2306b4\",\"definition\":\"\u003cp class=\\\"definition\\\"\u003eName of a \u003cspan data-glossary-id=\\\"UT22084-051-003-56\\\"\u003etathāgata\u003c/span\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\",\"names\":{\"english\":\"Yaśas\",\"tibetan\":\"གྲགས་པ།\",\"sanskrit\":\"yaśas\",\"pali\":\"\",\"chinese\":\"\",\"wylie\":\"grags pa\"}}]}]\n"])</script><div hidden id="S:5"><div dir="ltr" data-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs" class="flex flex-col w-full gap-0 @container/sidebar"><div class="sticky top-0 pt-1 pb-2 z-10 w-full rounded-t bg-background overflow-x-auto text-center"><div role="tablist" aria-orientation="horizontal" data-slot="tabs-list" class="bg-background gap-1 sm:gap-3 h-10 items-center justify-center sm:p-1 w-fit px-6 inline-flex mx-auto rounded-none" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" style="outline:none"><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="true" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-endnotes" data-state="active" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-endnotes" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Notes</button><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-glossary" data-state="inactive" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-glossary" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Glossary</button><button type="button" role="tab" aria-selected="false" aria-controls="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-bibliography" data-state="inactive" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-bibliography" data-slot="tabs-trigger" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center whitespace-nowrap px-1 py-0.75 text-sm data-[state=active]:font-semibold ring-offset-background transition-all focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 disabled:pointer-events-none disabled:opacity-50 bg-background text-foreground border-b-2 border-transparent data-[state=active]:border-primary-300 decoration-primary-25 hover:text-primary hover:border-primary/20 hover:cursor-pointer" tabindex="-1" data-orientation="horizontal" data-radix-collection-item="">Biblio</button></div></div><div class="px-2"><div class="overflow-auto md:h-[calc(100vh-8.5rem)] h-[calc(100vh-4rem)] rounded bg-surface"><div class="rounded ps-10 pe-4 max-w-readable mx-auto"><div data-state="active" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-endnotes" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-endnotes" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 data-[state=inactive]:hidden" style="animation-duration:0s"><div class="h-0"></div><div></div><div class="h-0"></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-4 pb-8"><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div><div class="flex gap-5"><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-6 w-6"></div><div class="animate-pulse rounded-md bg-foreground/10 h-32 grow"></div></div></div></div><div data-state="inactive" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-glossary" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-glossary" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 pb-8 data-[state=inactive]:hidden"><div class="flex flex-col w-full"><div id="glossary" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2lanpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-5 mt-6">g.</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><h2 class="font-serif font-light text-primary scroll-m-20 text-xl @c/sidebar:mt-4 mt-6 @c/sidebar:pb-2 pb-3 @c/sidebar:text-left text-center section-title">Glossary</h2></div></div><div class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-6"><div id="f0a03a9f-d197-4f62-889f-fd85bd047067" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_10d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Āditya­saṃbhava</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">nyi ma’i ’byung</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཉི་མའི་འབྱུང་།</span></li><li class="italic">āditya­saṃbhava</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="582a1227-33ce-4cf9-9d02-ca6a279fa9c1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_10l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Ajita</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mi pham</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མི་ཕམ།</span></li><li class="italic">ajita</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span>. Not to be confused with <em class="foreign text-wy" lang="bo-LATN">mgon po mi pham</em>, Maitreya.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="289fcb66-d5fb-47c3-8021-0a36cecfc88d" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_10t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Akṣobhya</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mi ’khrugs pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མི་འཁྲུགས་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">akṣobhya</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>Lit. “Not Disturbed” or “Immovable One.” The buddha in the eastern realm of Abhirati. A well-known buddha in Mahāyāna, regarded in the higher tantras as the head of one of the five buddha families, the vajra family in the east.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1155anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Amitābha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od dpag med</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་དཔག་མེད།</span></li><li class="italic">amitābha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Buddha associated with <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-170">Sukhāvatī</span>; buddha of the western direction; principal buddha of the Pure Land tradition; as the <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span> Dharmākara, he made forty-eight original vows (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">praṇidhāna</em>) to bring beings to enlightenment, thus establishing <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-170">Sukhāvatī</span> for their benefit; in tantrism he is one of the five dhyāni-buddhas and is associated with the aggregate of notions (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">saṃjñā­skandha</em>).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="2035d5ec-b30a-4ca2-b0ae-0868fb827fcd" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_11d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.5</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Amitadhvaja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rgyal msthan dpag med</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རྒྱལ་མསཐན་དཔག་མེད།</span></li><li class="italic">amitadhvaja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="5539c34a-3c5f-4958-a1f3-03d9ac386042" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_11l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.6</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Amitaskandha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">phung po dpag med</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཕུང་པོ་དཔག་མེད།</span></li><li class="italic">amitaskandha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="016abcba-d2ad-4141-a0c4-a1630608c46a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_11t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.7</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Amitāyus</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">tshe dpag med</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཚེ་དཔག་མེད།</span></li><li class="italic">amitāyus</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Buddha especially associated with life energy and long life; the sambhogakāya aspect of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-97">Amitābha</span>. Also a name of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-97">Amitābha</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="bec64dc6-b515-4d47-9b60-1709b8279767" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1255anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.8</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Anaṃtavīrya</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">brtson ’grus mtha’ yas</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བརྩོན་འགྲུས་མཐའ་ཡས།</span></li><li class="italic">anaṃtavīrya</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="0446e177-94b7-4a9e-b711-96fcb9641820" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_12d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.9</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Ānanda</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">kun dga’ bo</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཀུན་དགའ་བོ།</span></li><li class="italic">ānanda</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>A major śrāvaka disciple and personal attendant of the Buddha Śākyamuni during the last twenty-five years of his life. He was a cousin of the Buddha (according to the <cite class="title break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Mahāvastu</cite>, he was a son of Śuklodana, one of the brothers of King Śuddhodana, which means he was a brother of Devadatta; other sources say he was a son of Amṛtodana, another brother of King Śuddhodana, which means he would have been a brother of Aniruddha).</p><p>Ānanda, having always been in the Buddha’s presence, is said to have memorized all the teachings he heard and is celebrated for having recited all the Buddha’s teachings by memory at the first council of the Buddhist saṅgha, thus preserving the teachings after the Buddha’s parinirvāṇa. The phrase “Thus did I hear at one time,” found at the beginning of the sūtras, usually stands for his recitation of the teachings. He became a patriarch after the passing of Mahākāśyapa.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="fd580cc8-2f2e-4ccc-918e-6d2c9f814259" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_12l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.10</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Anikṣiptadhura</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">brtson pa’i mi ’dor</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བརྩོན་པའི་མི་འདོར།</span></li><li class="italic">anikṣiptadhura</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="599e0a5f-bd97-4b1d-a66d-deaf0cc92f50" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_12t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.11</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Aniruddha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ma ’gag pa, ’gags pa med pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མ་འགག་པ།, འགགས་པ་མེད་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">aniruddha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="69c51647-a349-4599-ae95-dbde5c407416" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1355anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.12</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">arhat</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dgra bcom pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">arhat</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>According to Buddhist tradition, one who is worthy of worship (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">pūjām arhati</em>), or one who has conquered the enemies, the mental afflictions (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">kleśa-ari-hata-vat</em>), and reached liberation from the cycle of rebirth and suffering. It is the fourth and highest of the four fruits attainable by śrāvakas. Also used as an epithet of the Buddha.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="2b04d627-b147-4363-9cc0-bf9ae96a744e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_13d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.13</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Bandé Yeshé Dé</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ban de ye shes sde</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བན་དེ་ཡེ་ཤེས་སྡེ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>Yeshé Dé (late eighth to early ninth century) was the most prolific translator of sūtras into Tibetan. Altogether he is credited with the translation of more than one hundred sixty sūtra translations and more than one hundred additional translations, mostly on tantric topics. In spite of Yeshé Dé’s great importance for the propagation of Buddhism in Tibet during the imperial era, only a few biographical details about this figure are known. Later sources describe him as a student of the Indian teacher Padmasambhava, and he is also credited with teaching both sūtra and tantra widely to students of his own. He was also known as Nanam Yeshé Dé, from the Nanam (<em class="foreign">sna nam</em>) clan.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="352fd1e2-6817-483a-8dc6-2a68cc2cc7dd" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_13l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.14</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">beryl</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bai dU rya</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བཻ་དཱུ་རྱ།</span></li><li class="italic">vaiḍūrya</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Precious/semiprecious stone; sometimes translated as lapis lazuli.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="ac3d1322-40ec-43b9-a027-cf2bbc3eac29" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_13t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.15</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">bhagavān</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bcom ldan ’das</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས།</span></li><li class="italic">bhagavat, bhagavān</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>In Buddhist literature, this is an epithet applied to buddhas, most often to Śākyamuni. The Sanskrit term generally means “possessing fortune,” but in specifically Buddhist contexts it implies that a buddha is in possession of six auspicious qualities (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bhaga</em>) associated with complete awakening. The Tibetan term‍—where <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bcom</em> is said to refer to “subduing” the four māras, <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">ldan</em> to “possessing” the great qualities of buddhahood, and <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">’das</em> to “going beyond” saṃsāra and nirvāṇa‍—possibly reflects the commentarial tradition where the Sanskrit <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bhagavat</em> is interpreted, in addition, as “one who destroys the four māras.” This is achieved either by reading <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bhagavat</em> as <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bhagnavat</em> (“one who broke”), or by tracing the word <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">bhaga</em> to the root <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">√bhañj</em> (“to break”).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="0100018f-0b4e-41c5-8907-42c281cb5be4" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1455anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.16</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Bharadvāja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bha ra dh+va dza</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བྷ་ར་དྷབ༹་ཛ།</span></li><li class="italic">bharadvāja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>; one of the sixteen sthavira <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span> (see “<span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-52">elder</span>”).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_14d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.17</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">bodhisattva</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">byang chub sems dpa’</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ།</span></li><li class="italic">bodhi­sattva</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>A being who is dedicated to the cultivation and fulfilment of the altruistic intention to attain perfect buddhahood, traversing the ten bodhisattva levels (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">daśabhūmi</em>, <em class="foreign text-wy" lang="bo-LATN">sa bcu</em>). Bodhisattvas purposely opt to remain within cyclic existence in order to liberate all sentient beings, instead of simply seeking personal freedom from suffering. In terms of the view, they realize both the selflessness of persons and the selflessness of phenomena.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="e9de2fe9-8140-41b9-89a0-010b6ef93ce6" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_14l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.18</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Brahmā</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">tshangs pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཚངས་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">brahmā</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Lord of the <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-144">Sahā world</span> (q.v.). Buddhists see <span class="ignore">Brahmā</span> as a god occupying a high position in cyclic existence, with a very long life and a great deal of power.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="337b83f8-04a2-4de9-b0d6-df74d2ba2e15" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_14t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.19</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Brahmaghoṣa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">tshangs pa’i dbyangs</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཚངས་པའི་དབྱངས།</span></li><li class="italic">brahmaghoṣa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="6c29513e-d408-4dce-bf30-bb680944251e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1555anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.20</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">branches of enlightenment</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">byang chub kyi yan lag</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བྱང་ཆུབ་ཀྱི་ཡན་ལག</span></li><li class="italic">bodhyaṅgāni</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">The branches of (1) authentic mindfulness, (2) authentic discrimination of dharmas, (3) authentic perseverance, (4) authentic joy, (5) authentic serenity, (6) authentic meditative absorption, and (7) authentic equanimity.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="300caeec-47cd-4381-9bf3-e0e64e410772" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_15d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.21</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Candra­sūrya­pradīpa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">nyi zla sgron ma</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཉི་ཟླ་སྒྲོན་མ།</span></li><li class="italic">candra­sūrya­pradīpa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="6e956151-b3eb-4769-a347-3f7728356ae4" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_15l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.22</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">coral</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">spug gi shing</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྤུག་གི་ཤིང་།</span></li><li class="italic">musāragalva</li></ul></div></div></div><div id="6ea36a2d-dfe5-4a59-89e6-122a54ef1e91" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_15t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.23</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Cūḍapanthaka</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lam phran bstan</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལམ་ཕྲན་བསྟན།</span></li><li class="italic">cūḍapanthaka</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>, one of the sixteen sthavira <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span> (see “<span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-52">elder</span>”).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="cc129426-225c-49dd-9d7d-d38b5291a7bb" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1655anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.24</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Dānaśīla</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dA na shI la</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དཱ་ན་ཤཱི་ལ།</span></li><li class="italic">dānaśīla</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Translator of the <cite class="title break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Sukhāvatī­vyūha­sūtra</cite>. </p></div></div></div></div><div id="4e9e0ffb-e9a8-43e5-b5d5-bea9bd8f9630" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_16d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.25</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Dharmadhara</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">chos ’dzin</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཆོས་འཛིན།</span></li><li class="italic">dharmadhara</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="442d4241-cda7-4bee-9120-0455941a9901" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_16l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.26</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Dharmadhvaja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">chos kyi rgyal mtshan</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཆོས་ཀྱི་རྒྱལ་མཚན།</span></li><li class="italic">dharmadhvaja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="d0f079d1-30f0-47be-8ac2-03bb80a06623" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_16t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.27</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Duṃdubhisvara­nirghoṣa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">duṃdubhisvara­nirghoṣa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="5784850c-540a-4a57-933a-5684a7764ec2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1755anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.28</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Duṣpradharṣa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rab tu thul dka’</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རབ་ཏུ་ཐུལ་དཀའ།</span></li><li class="italic">duṣpradharṣa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="44d992ce-75e8-4352-894d-0a1badff5874" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_17d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.29</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">elder</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">gnas brtan</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གནས་བརྟན།</span></li><li class="italic">sthavira</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">The term is used to designate a senior monk. The sixteen great <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span>, or sixteen noble <span class="ignore">elders</span> (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">āryasthavira</em>), were the successors of the Buddha’s teaching after he passed. They promised to preserve the teaching until the coming of the future Buddha Maitreya. They are on the path of seeing of the <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span> path. Each <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span> lived in a specific place: (1) Aṅgaja on Mt. Kailash; (2) <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-91">Ajita</span> in the Crystal Wood of Sages; (3) Vanavāsin on Mt. Saptaparṇa; (4) Mahākālika in Tāmradvīpa; (5) Vajrīputra in Siṃhaladvīpa; (6) Śrībhadra on Yamunādvīpa; (7) Kanakavatsa in Kashmir; (8) Kanakabharadvāja in the western continent of Godānīya; (9) Bakula in the northern continent of Uttarakuru; (10) <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-84">Rāhula</span> in Priyaṅgudvīpa; (11) <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-81">Cūḍapanthaka</span> on Mt. Gṛdhrakūṭa; (12) Piṇḍolabharadvāja in the eastern continent of Pūrvavideha; (13) Mahāpanthaka in Trayatriṃśa; (14) Nāgasena on Mt. <span class="ignore">Meru</span>; (15) Gopaka on Mt. Bhihula; and (16) Abhedya in the Himālayas.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="199e0291-ee9c-427a-8e31-6e47ef322b42" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_17l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.30</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">emerald</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rdo’i snying po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རྡོའི་སྙིང་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">aśmagarbha</li></ul></div></div></div><div id="c319c56a-27d7-4a3a-ac85-57e9b9b42b30" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_17t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.31</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">five degenerations</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">snyigs ma lnga</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྙིགས་མ་ལྔ།</span></li><li class="italic">pañcakaṣāya</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">The <span class="ignore">five degenerations</span> are (1) the degeneration of life span, (2) the degeneration of views, (3) the degeneration of the afflictions, (4) the degeneration of beings, and (5) the degeneration of the era.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="0fcc400e-0eb1-4dba-9bb0-2dc2eca1ef35" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1855anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.32</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">fully awakened</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mngon par rdzogs par sangs rgyas</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མངོན་པར་རྫོགས་པར་སངས་རྒྱས།</span></li><li class="italic">abhisaṃbuddha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">A person who has manifested the complete enlightenment of a buddha of the Greater Vehicle.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="7bd94653-51b8-490d-abe2-7858e6e9042f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_18d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.33</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Gandhahastin</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">spos kyi glang po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྤོས་ཀྱི་གླང་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">gandhahastin</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="be55b2b6-ff5f-4ffe-ba61-68e70f3cad76" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_18l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.34</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Gandhaprabhāsa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">spos ’od</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྤོས་འོད།</span></li><li class="italic">gandhaprabhāsa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="a91dd7af-e500-43dc-a760-ae1cf5fc09be" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_18t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.35</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">gandharva</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dri za</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དྲི་ཟ།</span></li><li class="italic">gandharva</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>A class of generally benevolent nonhuman beings who inhabit the skies, sometimes said to inhabit fantastic cities in the clouds, and more specifically to dwell on the eastern slopes of Mount Meru, where they are ruled by the Great King Dhṛtarāṣṭra. They are most renowned as celestial musicians who serve the gods. In the Abhidharma, the term is also used to refer to the mental body assumed by sentient beings during the intermediate state between death and rebirth. Gandharvas are said to live on fragrances (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">gandha</em>) in the desire realm, hence the Tibetan translation <em class="foreign text-wy" lang="bo-LATN">dri za</em>, meaning “scent eater.”</p></div></div></div></div><div id="2bdd0277-a2ca-4881-a150-052e5313a29e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1955anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.36</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Gandhottama</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">spos mchog</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྤོས་མཆོག</span></li><li class="italic">gandhottama</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="efcf655a-f029-473a-981e-65188b267821" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_19d5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.37</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Gavāṃpati</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ba lang bdag</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བ་ལང་བདག</span></li><li class="italic">gavāṃpati</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>; one of the Buddha’s five close <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span> disciples. He took ordination from the Buddha and then became a disciple of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-74">Śāriputra</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="a4978597-e1f4-4673-bddf-53b064a56656" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_19l5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.38</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Jālinīprabha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dra ba can gyi ’od</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དྲ་བ་ཅན་གྱི་འོད།</span></li><li class="italic">jālenīprabha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="3f9da289-6926-4284-8fc0-c88a5c8710b8" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_19t5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.39</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Jeta’s Grove, Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rgyal bu rgyal byed kyi tshal mgon med zas sbyin gyi kun dga’ ra ba</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རྒྱལ་བུ་རྒྱལ་བྱེད་ཀྱི་ཚལ་མགོན་མེད་ཟས་སྦྱིན་གྱི་ཀུན་དགའ་ར་བ།</span></li><li class="italic">jetavanam anāthapiṇḍadasyārāmaḥ</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">One of the first Buddhist monasteries, located in a park outside Śrāvastī, the capital of the ancient kingdom of Kośala in northern India. This park was originally owned by Prince Jeta, hence the name Jetavana, meaning Jeta’s grove. The wealthy merchant Anāthapiṇḍada, wishing to offer it to the Buddha, sought to buy it from him, but the prince, not wishing to sell, said he would only do so if Anāthapiṇḍada covered the entire property with gold coins. Anāthapiṇḍada agreed, and managed to cover all of the park except the entrance, hence the name Anāthapiṇḍadasyārāmaḥ, meaning Anāthapiṇḍada’s park. The place is usually referred to in the sūtras as “Jetavana, Anāthapiṇḍada’s park,” and according to the <cite class="title break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Saṃghabhedavastu </cite> the Buddha used Prince Jeta’s name in first place because that was Prince Jeta’s own unspoken wish while Anāthapiṇḍada was offering the park. Inspired by the occasion and the Buddha’s use of his name, Prince Jeta then offered the rest of the property and had an entrance gate built. The Buddha specifically instructed those who recite the sūtras to use Prince Jeta’s name in first place to commemorate the mutual effort of both benefactors. </p><p class="definition">Anāthapiṇḍada built residences for the monks, to house them during the monsoon season, thus creating the first Buddhist monastery. It was one of the Buddha’s main residences, where he spent around nineteen rainy season retreats, and it was therefore the setting for many of the Buddha’s discourses and events. According to the travel accounts of Chinese monks, it was still in use as a Buddhist monastery in the early fifth century <span class="small-caps">ᴄᴇ</span>, but by the sixth century it had been reduced to ruins. </p></div></div></div></div><div id="cc0bc8b5-a812-4464-9f51-013a41def137" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1a55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.40</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Kālodāyin</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’char byed nag po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འཆར་བྱེད་ནག་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">kālodāyin</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="71de5a26-899a-49b1-af00-bf2dd62d6a9e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ad5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.41</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Lord of Death</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">gshin rje</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གཤིན་རྗེ།</span></li><li class="italic">yama</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Lord of Death.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="aec33c7d-3cbe-4692-8aee-9f0d9f44b944" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1al5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.42</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahākapphiṇa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ka pi na chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཀ་པི་ན་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahākapphiṇa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="b3b06ad4-5d91-4a74-aeb1-55b7caba1f9e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1at5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.43</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahākāśyapa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od srung chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་སྲུང་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahākāśyapa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>, one of the most important followers of the Buddha.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="c712ec91-f592-400b-8c25-8be19053d214" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1b55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.44</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahā­kātyāyana</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">kA tyA’i bu chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཀཱ་ཏྱཱའི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahā­kātyāyana</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="0bc0e51f-934d-4dea-821a-be5424257020" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1bd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.45</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahākauṣṭhila</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">gsus po che</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གསུས་པོ་ཆེ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahākauṣṭhila</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="08c2549e-ad1b-43d3-8d34-d4c43ae79953" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1bl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.46</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahā­maudgalyāyana</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">maud gal gyi bu chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མཽད་གལ་གྱི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahā­maudgalyāyana</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>, one of the most important followers of the Buddha.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="c44d3b6a-16ca-4e2f-b5b2-72b27d50179f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1bt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.47</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahāmeru</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lhun po chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལྷུན་པོ་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahāmeru</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="668ec6ff-23f8-448a-a18e-670b1380e40c" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1c55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.48</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahā­meru­prabhāsa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lhun po chen po snang ba</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལྷུན་པོ་ཆེན་པོ་སྣང་བ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahā­meru­prabhāsa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="efbce404-5ab0-4fa7-a273-a680ddb28630" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1cd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.49</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahāprabha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od chen</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་ཆེན།</span></li><li class="italic">mahāprabha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="a44dc3c6-c701-4dc0-95d9-7f38e1e9e5d1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1cl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.50</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mahārciskandha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od ’phro’i phung po chen po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་འཕྲོའི་ཕུང་པོ་ཆེན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">mahārciskandha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="3467117e-28dd-43da-86cb-596f3d7434dc" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ct5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.51</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">mandārava</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">man dA ra ba</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མན་དཱ་ར་བ།</span></li><li class="italic">mandārava</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>One of the five trees of Indra’s paradise, its heavenly flowers often rain down in salutation of the buddhas and bodhisattvas and are said to be very bright and aromatic, gladdening the hearts of those who see them. In our world, it is a tree native to India, <em class="foreign">Erythrina indica</em> or <em class="foreign">Erythrina variegata</em>, commonly known as the Indian coral tree, mandarava tree, flame tree, and tiger’s claw. In the early spring, before its leaves grow, the tree is fully covered in large flowers, which are rich in nectar and attract many birds. Although the most widespread coral tree has red crimson flowers, the color of the blossoms is not usually mentioned in the sūtras themselves, and it may refer to some other kinds, like the rarer <em class="foreign">Erythrina indica alba</em>, which boasts white flowers.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="c652489b-6d36-434b-89d4-db8cf895539e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1d55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.52</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mañjudhvaja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mañjudhvaja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="30bbcb97-b2e0-49a3-90f9-d92930f4a899" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1dd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.53</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Mañjuśrī</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’jam dpal gzhon nu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འཇམ་དཔལ་གཞོན་ནུ།</span></li><li class="italic">mañjuśrī</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>Mañjuśrī is one of the “eight close sons of the Buddha” and a bodhisattva who embodies wisdom. He is a major figure in the Mahāyāna sūtras, appearing often as an interlocutor of the Buddha. In his most well-known iconographic form, he is portrayed bearing the sword of wisdom in his right hand and a volume of the <cite class="title break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Prajñā­pāramitā­sūtra</cite> in his left. To his name, Mañjuśrī, meaning “Gentle and Glorious One,” is often added the epithet Kumārabhūta, “having a youthful form.” He is also called Mañjughoṣa, Mañjusvara, and Pañcaśikha.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="50ea35ec-22af-401a-8781-677dae8da4b2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1dl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.54</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Meru</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lhun po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལྷུན་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">meru</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="e9937693-da05-4201-ab76-086c56101a86" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1dt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.55</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Merudhvaja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lhun po rgyal mtshan</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལྷུན་པོ་རྒྱལ་མཚན།</span></li><li class="italic">merudhvaja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="785b6780-ca7f-4127-96b4-322f31755f8c" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1e55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.56</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Merupradīpa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">lhun po’i sgron ma</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ལྷུན་པོའི་སྒྲོན་མ།</span></li><li class="italic">merupradīpa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="963ca73b-4128-4973-9074-fb96471f50e8" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ed5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.57</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Nakṣatrarāja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">skar m’i rgyal po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྐར་མའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">nakṣatrarāja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="6ec612e0-8c00-4d85-ba39-15ee82bb32e2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1el5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.58</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Nanda</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dga’ bo</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དགའ་བོ།</span></li><li class="italic">nanda</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="ef9e56ec-eb73-48fc-ada9-69370cc7a2fa" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1et5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.59</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Nityodyukta</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rtag tu btson</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རྟག་ཏུ་བཙོན།</span></li><li class="italic">nityodyukta</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="e4055571-7f0c-4b3e-b35e-962919a4230d" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1f55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.60</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">not regress</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">phyir mi ldog pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཕྱིར་མི་ལྡོག་པ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">A stage on the <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattva</span> path where the practitioner will never turn back, or be turned back, from progress toward the full awakening of a buddha.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="dc33eabf-781b-46a7-b33f-222eda12328a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1fd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.61</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">palm tree</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">shing ta la</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཤིང་ཏ་ལ།</span></li><li class="italic">tāla</li></ul></div></div></div><div id="053d45ba-7799-42ef-9329-e5de8f15985f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1fl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.62</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">perfectly and fully enlightened buddha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">yang dag par rdzogs pa’i sangs rgyas</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཡང་དག་པར་རྫོགས་པའི་སངས་རྒྱས།</span></li><li class="italic">samyaksaṃbuddha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">A term used to emphasize the superiority of buddhahood when contrasted with the achievement of the <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span> and pratyekabuddhas. A samyaksaṃbuddha is considered superior by virtue of his compassionate activity, his omniscience, and his ten special <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-63">powers</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="51f52255-edd6-4293-bc12-e2cf1728c67b" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ft5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.63</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">powers</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">dbang po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དབང་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">indriya</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">The five powers, or faculties, are those of (1) faith, (2) perseverence, (3) mindfulness, (4) meditative absorption or samādhi, and (5) wisdom or prajñā.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="cbf396c1-57a6-4983-8aef-940ca730e637" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1g55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.64</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Prabhākara</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od kyi byung gnas</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་ཀྱི་བྱུང་གནས།</span></li><li class="italic">prabhākara</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="3ba91505-bc0f-4713-a614-61ffedacfce0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1gd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.65</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Rāhula</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">sgra gcan zin</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྒྲ་གཅན་ཟིན།</span></li><li class="italic">rāhula</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>, one of the sixteen sthavira <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span> (see “<span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-52">elder</span>”).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="917c67f3-965c-4e0c-aa13-bf57faab3698" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1gl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.66</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Ratnaketu</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rin po che’i tog</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་ཏོག</span></li><li class="italic">ratnaketu</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="63a0e2a5-2f58-4cad-8c46-d472a0c8381a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1gt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.67</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rin chen me tog shin tu rgyas pa’i rigs</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རིན་ཆེན་མེ་ཏོག་ཤིན་ཏུ་རྒྱས་པའི་རིགས།</span></li><li class="italic">ratna­kusuma­saṃpuṣpita­gotra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="b3be1416-815c-464a-a552-1f8f5a577795" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1h55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.68</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Ratnotpalaśrī</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">rin chen ud pa la’i dpal</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རིན་ཆེན་ཨུད་པ་ལའི་དཔལ།</span></li><li class="italic">ratnotpalaśrī</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="d7eab3d7-6add-4eff-b3b9-d30ececf3242" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1hd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.69</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Revata</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">nam gru</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ནམ་གྲུ།</span></li><li class="italic">revata</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="5d788529-5cfd-445d-a109-2c736276ff68" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1hl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.70</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sahā world</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mi mjed, mi mjed kyi ’jig rten</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མི་མཇེད་ཀྱི་འཇིག་རྟེན།, མི་མཇེད།</span></li><li class="italic">sahā, sahā­loka­dhatu</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">This universe of ours, presided over by <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-96">Brahmā</span>. The term is variously interpreted as meaning the world of suffering, of endurance, of fearlessness, or of concomitance (of karmic cause and effect).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="1345f24e-bf84-468e-b250-5a1fec39c3d9" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ht5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.71</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śakra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">brgya byin</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བརྒྱ་བྱིན།</span></li><li class="italic">śakra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>The lord of the gods in the Heaven of the Thirty-Three (<em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">trāyastriṃśa</em>). Alternatively known as Indra, the deity that is called “lord of the gods” dwells on the summit of Mount Sumeru and wields the thunderbolt. The Tibetan translation <em class="foreign text-wy" lang="bo-LATN">brgya byin</em> (meaning “one hundred sacrifices”) is based on an etymology that <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">śakra</em> is an abbreviation of <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">śata-kratu</em>, one who has performed a hundred sacrifices. Each world with a central Sumeru has a Śakra. Also known by other names such as Kauśika, Devendra, and Śacipati. </p></div></div></div></div><div id="d06e0aac-8497-4476-acb3-e2aa986048fa" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1i55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.72</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sālendrarāja</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">sA la’i dbang po’i rgyal po</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སཱ་ལའི་དབང་པོའི་རྒྱལ་པོ།</span></li><li class="italic">sālendrarāja</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1id5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.73</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śāriputra</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">shA ri’i bu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ།</span></li><li class="italic">śāriputra</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>One of the principal śrāvaka disciples of the Buddha, he was renowned for his discipline and for having been praised by the Buddha as foremost of the wise (often paired with Maudgalyā­yana, who was praised as foremost in the capacity for miraculous powers). His father, Tiṣya, to honor Śāriputra’s mother, Śārikā, named him Śāradvatīputra, or, in its contracted form, Śāriputra, meaning “Śārikā’s Son.”</p></div></div></div></div><div id="0ee143cc-6dde-417f-bcd6-5a42b7216b18" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1il5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.74</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sarvārthadarśa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mthong ba don yod</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མཐོང་བ་དོན་ཡོད།</span></li><li class="italic">sarvārthadarśa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="babb1949-536c-4429-8401-6734edce8fe4" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1it5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.75</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Siṃha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">seng ge</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སེང་གེ</span></li><li class="italic">siṃha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="a228dd64-edf0-47f9-8d90-55883408ec6a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1j55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.76</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">śrāvaka</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">nyan thos</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཉན་ཐོས།</span></li><li class="italic">śrāvaka</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Hīnayāna practitioner of the first turning of the wheel of the Dharma on the four noble truths, who realizes the suffering inherent in saṃsāra and focuses on understanding that there is no independent self. By conquering disturbing emotions, he liberates himself, attaining first the stage of stream enterer at the path of seeing, followed by the stage of once-returner who will be reborn only one more time, and then the stage of non-returner who will no longer be reborn into saṃsāra. The final goal is to become an <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>. These four stages are also known as the “four results of spiritual practice.”</p></div></div></div></div><div id="61aa044f-aaea-4d30-b1ae-efbd23d8aaa4" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1jd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.77</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śrāvastī</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">mnyan yod</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">མཉན་ཡོད།</span></li><li class="italic">śrāvastī</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>During the life of the Buddha, Śrāvastī was the capital city of the powerful kingdom of Kośala, ruled by King Prasenajit, who became a follower and patron of the Buddha. It was also the hometown of Anāthapiṇḍada, the wealthy patron who first invited the Buddha there, and then offered him a park known as Jetavana, Prince Jeta’s Grove, which became one of the first Buddhist monasteries. The Buddha is said to have spent about twenty-five rainy seasons with his disciples in Śrāvastī, thus it is named as the setting of numerous events and teachings. It is located in present-day Uttar Pradesh in northern India.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="f50cfb2f-a0d3-4937-abc7-32f85ec32a25" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1jl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.78</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">strengths</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">stobs</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">སྟོབས།</span></li><li class="italic">bala</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">For the five <span class="ignore">strengths</span>, see “<span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-63">powers</span>.” The ten <span class="ignore">strengths</span> can refer either to one set of ten qualities of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgatas</span>, or to a different list of ten <span class="ignore">strengths</span> of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-55">bodhisattvas</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="eb18fa0e-9f40-4ab1-87f5-8835b07d99a7" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1jt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.79</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Śuddha­raśmi­prabha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">’od zer dag pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">འོད་ཟེར་དག་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">śuddha­raśmi­prabha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1k55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.80</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sukhāvatī</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bde ba can</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བདེ་བ་ཅན།</span></li><li class="italic">sukhāvatī</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Meaning “the delightful” or “the land of delight,” the name of the buddhafield of <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-97">Amitābha</span> / <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-98">Amitāyus</span>, in the western direction from our world.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="55dd1b30-2b7f-484f-8b2a-f54eb9c8ad6a" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1kd5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.81</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sumerukalpa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ri rab lta bu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">རི་རབ་ལྟ་བུ།</span></li><li class="italic">sumerukalpa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1kl5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.82</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">tathāgata</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">de bzhin gshegs pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">དེ་བཞིན་གཤེགས་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">tathāgata</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p>A frequently used synonym for <em class="emph">buddha</em>. According to different explanations, it can be read as <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">tathā-gata</em>, literally meaning “one who has thus gone,” or as <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">tathā-āgata</em>, “one who has thus come.” <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Gata</em>, though literally meaning “gone,” is a past passive participle used to describe a state or condition of existence. <em class="foreign break text-sa" lang="sa-LATN">Tatha­(tā)</em>, often rendered as “suchness” or “thusness,” is the quality or condition of things as they really are, which cannot be conveyed in conceptual, dualistic terms. Therefore, this epithet is interpreted in different ways, but in general it implies one who has departed in the wake of the buddhas of the past, or one who has manifested the supreme awakening dependent on the reality that does not abide in the two extremes of existence and quiescence. It is also often used as a specific epithet of the Buddha Śākyamuni.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="189fde85-23ea-4ae0-8633-ec042c2d08db" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1kt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.83</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Tathāgata Dharma</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">chos</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཆོས།</span></li><li class="italic">dharma</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="19c87c79-3035-4fbc-b20a-8c66a6846f26" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1l55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.84</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">unsurpassable, completely perfect enlightenment</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">bla na med pa yang dag par rdzogs pa’i byang chub</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བླ་ན་མེད་པ་ཡང་དག་པར་རྫོགས་པའི་བྱང་ཆུབ།</span></li><li class="italic">anuttara­samyak­saṃbodhi</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">An enlightenment that is authentically complete.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="5d519b6d-47d9-4cd5-9360-8858e776cd28" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ld5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.85</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Vaiśvānara­nirghoṣa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">thams cad sgrol ba’i dbyangs sgrol</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཐམས་ཅད་སྒྲོལ་བའི་དབྱངས་སྒྲོལ།</span></li><li class="italic">vaiśvānara­nirghoṣa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="6c8e57e3-13aa-49fd-9c28-46ccb755085f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ll5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.86</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Vakula</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">ba ku la</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">བ་ཀུ་ལ།</span></li><li class="italic">bakula</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition"><span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-53">Śrāvaka</span> <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhat</span>; one of the sixteen sthavira <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-54">arhats</span> (see “<span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-52">elder</span>”).</p></div></div></div></div><div id="5dca12bb-41c2-4344-b250-004caab85340" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1lt5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.87</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">water possessing the eight qualities</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">yan lag brgyad dang ldan pa’i chu</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">ཡན་ལག་བརྒྱད་དང་ལྡན་པའི་ཆུ།</span></li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">The eight qualities of water: (1) sweet-tasting; (2) cool; (3) soft; (4) light; (5) transparent; (6) clean; (7) not harmful to the throat; and (8) beneficial to the stomach.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="8d5a2c19-5565-4b33-8401-8b7a666b93c2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1m55anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.88</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Yaśaḥprabha</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">grags pa’i ’od</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གྲགས་པའི་འོད།</span></li><li class="italic">yaśaḥprabha</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="34c79710-b026-450f-82c9-1d14d9f55f56" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1md5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.89</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Yaśaḥprabhāsa</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">grags ’od</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གྲགས་འོད།</span></li><li class="italic">yaśaḥprabhāsa</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div><div id="c0a5489f-9a0b-40ae-8922-9cb9dae9f0db" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ml5anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">g.90</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="flex gap-1 flex-col p-0 @c/sidebar:-mt-0.5"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Yaśas</div><ul class="ml-4 list-disc"><li class="italic">grags pa</li><li class="pt-1"><span class="font-tibetan text-base">གྲགས་པ།</span></li><li class="italic">yaśas</li></ul><div class="glossary-instance-definition"><p class="definition">Name of a <span data-glossary-id="UT22084-051-003-56">tathāgata</span>.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-state="inactive" data-orientation="horizontal" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-trigger-bibliography" id="radix-_R_2npftt6btb_-content-bibliography" tabindex="0" data-slot="tabs-content" class="mt-2 ring-offset-background focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-ring focus-visible:ring-offset-2 pb-8 data-[state=inactive]:hidden"><div class="flex flex-col w-full"><div id="bibliography" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2nanpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-5 mt-6">b.</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><h2 class="font-serif font-light text-primary scroll-m-20 text-xl @c/sidebar:mt-4 mt-6 @c/sidebar:pb-2 pb-3 @c/sidebar:text-left text-center section-title">Bibliography</h2></div></div><div class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-6"><div class="flex flex-col gap-4"><div id="Tibetan Texts-0" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5d7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-0.5 mt-4">b.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Tibetan Texts</div></div></div><div id="13157476-771c-42e0-ac1e-4afe042e89d1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_16d7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>’phags pa bde ba can gyi bkod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo</em>. Toh 115, Degé Kangyur vol. 51 (mdo sde, ja), folios 195.b–200.b. </p></div></div></div><div id="5e73ac8e-7b8b-4a36-8409-bf226d470b6c" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ad7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>’phags pa bde ba can gyi bkod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo</em>. bka’ ’gyur (dpe bsdur ma) [Comparative Edition of the Kangyur], krung go’i bod rig pa zhib ’jug ste gnas kyi bka’ bstan dpe sdur khang (The Tibetan Tripitaka Collation Bureau of the China Tibetology Research Center). 108 volumes. Beijing: krung go’i bod rig pa dpe skrun khang (China Tibetology Publishing House), 2006–9, vol. 51, pp. 532–42. </p></div></div></div><div id="71dd1ef8-c7be-43c2-9fc0-d9a79dcfd036" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1ed7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Ha’o wun zhon and To’u tshun chi, eds. <em>bod rgya shan sbyar gyi shes bya’i rnam grangs kun btus tshig mdzod</em>. Beijing: mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Minorities Publishing House), 1987. </p></div></div></div><div id="af4e9517-f090-45f5-8086-7f9f182882a3" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1id7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>bde smon phyogs bsgrigs</em> [<em>The Collection of Prayers for Sukhāvatī</em>]. Chengdu: si khron mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Sichuan Minorities Publishing House), 2007.</p></div></div></div><div id="b7da1c0e-95fb-4ac2-b8ad-199c916d4e89" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1md7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.5</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>mkhas grub rā ga a syas mdzad pa’i rnam dag bde chen zhing gi smon lam</em> [<em>Long Prayer for Sukhāvatī</em>]. Chengdu: si khron mi rigs dpe skrun khang (Sichuan Minorities Publishing House), 2007.</p></div></div></div><div id="a9a2cda0-117f-4c41-b3db-d469776ebbe1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_1qd7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.1.6</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>’phags pa bzang po spyod pa’i smon lam gyi rgyal po</em> [<em><a href="https://read.84000.co/translation/toh1095.html">The Noble King of Prayers of Good Conduct</a></em>]. Toh 1095, Degé Kangyur, vol. 101 (gzungs ’dus, waM), folios 262.a–266.b.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-4"><div id="Sanskrit Texts-1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5l7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-0.5 mt-4">b.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Sanskrit Texts</div></div></div><div id="e6ac3f44-7544-4d1c-9fc4-75a9a70037ec" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_el7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.2.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p> <em>Ārya­sukhāvatī­vyūha­nāma­mahā­yāna­sūtra</em>. <a href="http://gretil.sub.uni-goettingen.de/gretil/1_sanskr/4_rellit/buddh/sukhvysu.htm">http://gretil.sub.uni-goettingen.de</a>. Accessed August 25, 2010.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="flex flex-col gap-4"><div id="Secondary Literature-2" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_5t7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4 @c/sidebar:mt-0.5 mt-4">b.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div class="text-secondary font-sans text-base font-bold">Secondary Literature</div></div></div><div id="873b2a46-fee1-422b-9b50-0f5e46892114" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_26t7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.1</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Epstein, Ronald, trans. <em>The Amitābha Sūtra</em>. Hsüan Hua, A General Explanation of the Buddha Speaks of Amitābha Sūtra. San Francisco: Buddhist Text Translation Society, 1974. <a href="http://online.sfsu.edu/~rone/Buddhism/amitabha.htm">online.sfsu.ed</a>.</p></div></div></div><div id="bbe6c22e-0b04-49ee-8ec4-d997b654f8d7" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2at7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.2</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Fujita, Kōtatsu. “Textual Origins of the <em>Kuan Wu-liang-shou ching</em>.” In <em>Chinese Buddhist Apocrypha</em>, edited by Robert E. Buswell, Jr., 149–173. Honolulu: University of Hawai’i Press, 1990.</p></div></div></div><div id="a58252d0-1ddd-4b36-82d4-2ce89cba7f58" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2et7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.3</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Gomez, Luis O. <em>Land of Bliss: The Paradise of the Buddha of Measureless Light; Sanskrit and Chinese Versions of the Sukhāvatīvyūha Sūtras.</em> Honolulu: University of Hawai’i Press, 1996.</p></div></div></div><div id="c05c270c-0f39-4789-b9e7-d459342c7cf1" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2it7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.4</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Hapatsch, Hischam A., trans. and ed. <em>Die Heiligen Schriften des Amitābha-Buddhismus: Das große Sukhāvatī-vyūha-Sūtra, Das kleine Sukhāvatī-vyūha-Sūtra, Das Meditationssūtra</em>. Berlin, 2007. <a href="http://www.littera.de/buecher/sukha.html">www.littera.de</a>. Accessed 2010.</p></div></div></div><div id="673a54ff-8f89-4e1a-8c15-8645b1885093" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2mt7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.5</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Müller, Max, and Bunyiu Nanjio, trans. “Āryasukhāvatīvyūhasūtra.” <em>Anecdota Oxoniensia: Aryan Series</em>. Vol. I, part II. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1883.</p></div></div></div><div id="187d3c3b-13ad-4feb-a277-10a496c54154" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2qt7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.6</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Nakamura, Hajime. <em>Indian Buddhism: A Survey with Bibliographical Notes</em>. Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass Publications, 1987.</p></div></div></div><div id="ac744700-8796-4c67-be00-187e3dc109f9" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_2ut7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.7</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Roberts, Peter Alan and Emily Bower, trans. <em><a href="http://read.84000.co/translation/UT22084-054-003.html">The Aparimitāyurjñāna Sūtra</a></em> (Toh 674). 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha, 2016. </p></div></div></div><div id="ca545715-4004-426a-9283-ef8199f9cd6f" class="relative scroll-mt-20"><button type="button" id="radix-_R_32t7anpftt6btb_" aria-haspopup="menu" aria-expanded="false" data-state="closed" class="absolute labeled -left-16 w-16 text-end hover:cursor-pointer whitespace-pre-line leading-4">b.3.8</button><div class="passage pl-6 @c/sidebar:pl-4"><div><p>Utsuki, Nishu. <em>The Smaller Sukhāvatīvyūha Sūtra or The Sūtra on the Buddha Amitāyus: Translated from the Chinese Version of Kumārajīva</em>. Kyoto: Educational Department of the West Hongwanji, 1924. <a href="http://web.mit.edu/stclair/www/smaller.html">web.mit.edu</a>.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>$RS("S:5","P:5")</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"24:I[916077,[\"/_next/static/chunks/2fb4b456dae69409.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/6165fecb8e0eae36.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/1cfd6a6ab8fe5d2f.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\",\"/_next/static/chunks/15d7387d42764915.js?dpl=dpl_C4kSSWFdt51TZQpmuYtxXgHAunY1\"],\"ReaderBodyPanel\"]\n25:Tc82,སངས་རྒྱས་དང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཐམས་\nཅད་ལ་ཕྱག་འཚལ་ལོ། །འདི་སྐད་བདག་གིས་ཐོས་པ་དུས་གཅིག་ན། བཅོམ་ལྡན་འདས་མཉན་ཡོད་ན། རྒྱལ་བུ་རྒྱལ་བྱེད་ཀྱི་ཚལ་མགོན་མེད་ཟས་སྦྱིན་གྱི་ཀུན་དགའ་ར་བ་ན། དགེ་སློང་སྟོང་ཉིས་བརྒྱ་ལྔ་བཅུའི་དགེ་སློང་གི་དགེ་འདུན་ཆེན་པོ་གནས་བརྟན་ཉན་ཐོས་\nཆེན་པོ་དགྲ་བཅོམ་པ་ཤ་སྟག་ལ་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། གནས་བརྟན་ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་དང་། མཽད་གལ་གྱི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། འོད་སྲུང་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། ཀཱ་ཏྱཱའི་བུ་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། ཀ་པི་ན་ཆེན་པོ་དང་། གསུས་པོ་ཆེ་དང་། ནམ་གྲུ་དང་། ལམ་ཕྲན་བསྟན་དང་། དགའ་བོ་དང་། ཀུན་དགའ་\nབོ་དང་། སྒྲ་གཅན་ཟིན་དང་། བ་ལང་བདག་དང་། བྷ་ར་དྷྭ་ཛི་དང་། འཆར་བྱེད་ནག་པོ་དང་། བ་ཀུ་ལ་དང་། མ་འགགས་པ་དང་། དེ་དག་དང་། ཉན་ཐོས་ཆེན་པོ་གཞན་དག་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་མང་པོ་ལ་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། འཇམ་དཔལ་[F.196.a]གཞོན་ནུར་གྱུར་པ་དང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་མི་ཕམ་པ་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་སྤོས་ཀྱི་གླང་པོ་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་རྟག་ཏུ་བརྩོན་དང་། བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་\nཆེན་པོ་བརྩོན་པ་མི་འདོར་བ་དང་། དེ་དག་དང་བྱང་ཆུབ་སེམས་དཔའ་སེམས་དཔའ་ཆེན་པོ་གཞན་མང་པོ་དག་དང་། ལྷའི་དབང་པོ་བརྒྱ་བྱིན་དང་། མི་མཇེད་ཀྱི་བདག་པོ་ཚངས་པ་དང་། དེ་དག་དང་ལྷ་བྱེ་བ་ཁྲག་ཁྲིག་འབུམ་ཕྲག་མང་པོ་གཞན་དག་དང་ཡང་ཐབས་ཅིག་ཏུ་\nབཞུགས་ཏེ། 26:Td67,ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་\nཁམས་བདེ་བ་ཅན་དེ་ན་སེམས་ཅན་རྣམས་ཀྱི་ལུས་ལ་སྡུག་བསྔལ་མེད། སེམས་ལ་སྡུག་བསྔལ་མེད་ཅིང་བདེ་བའི་རྒྱུ་ཚད་མེད་པར་ཡོད་དེ། དེའི་ཕྱིར་འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཁམས་བདེ་བ་ཅན་ཞེ"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"ས་བྱའོ། །ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་གཞན་ཡང་འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཁམས་བདེ་བ་ཅན་ནི་ཁ་ཁྱེར་རིམ་པ་\nབདུན་དང་། ཤིང་ཏ་ལའི་ཕྲེང་བ་རིམ་པ་བདུན་དང་། དྲིལ་བུ་གཡེར་ཀའི་དྲ་བ་རྣམས་ཀྱིས་ཀུན་ནས་ཡོངས་སུ་བསྐོར་བ། བཀྲ་བ་བལྟ་ན་སྡུག་པའོ། །ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་ཞིང་དེ་ནི་རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བཞི་ལ་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། གསེར་དང་། དངུལ་དང་། བཻ་དཱུརྱ་དང་། ཤེལ་\nདང་། རྣམ་པ་དེ་ལྟ་བུའི་སངས་རྒྱས་ཀྱི་ཞིང་གི་ཡོན་ཏན་བཀོད་པ་དག་གིས་ལེགས་པར་བརྒྱན་པའོ། །ཤཱ་རིའི་བུ་གཞན་ཡང་འཇིག་རྟེན་གྱི་ཁམས་བདེ་བ་ཅན་ན་རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བདུན་གྱི་རྫིང་ཡན་ལག་བརྒྱད་དང་ལྡན་པའི་ཆུས་ཡོངས་སུ་གང་བ། རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་པད་མས་ཁེབས་[F.196.b]པ། བྱ་རོག་གིས་བཏུང་དུ་རུང་བར་ཁ་ད་ཆད་དུ་གྱུར་པ་གསེར་གྱི་བྱེ་མ་བདལ་བ་དག་ཡོད་དེ། རྫིང་དེ་དག་གི་ཕྱོགས་བཞི་ཀུན་ན་ཐེམ་སྐས་བཀྲ་བ། བལྟ་ན་སྡུག་པ། གསེར་དང་། དངུལ་དང་། བཻ་དཱུརྱ་དང་། ཤེལ་དང་། རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བཞི་ལས་བྱས་པ་བཞི་བཞི་\nཡོད་དོ། །རྫིང་དེ་དག་གི་འགྲམ་ན་རིན་པོ་ཆེའི་ཤིང་ལྗོན་པ་རིན་པོ་ཆེ་སྣ་བདུན་ལ་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། གསེར་དང་། དངུལ་དང་། བཻ་དཱུརྱ་དང་། ཤེལ་དང་། མུ་ཏིག་དམར་པོ་དང་། རྡོའི་སྙིང་པོ་དང་། སྤུག་གི་ཤིང་བཀྲ་བ། བལྟ་ན་སྡུག་པ་དག་སྐྱེས་སོ། །རྫིང་དེ་དག་ཀུན་ནས་པད་\nམ་སྐྱེས་པ་འདི་ལྟ་སྟེ། "])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,"17:[\"$\",\"$L24\",null,{\"titles\":[{\"uuid\":\"a73b8946-8962-4f88-9d2f-4e988bce740b\",\"title\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"86bee3a8-a7e6-44ad-b6e0-776b3bbdc046\",\"title\":\"Sukhāvatī­vyūha\",\"language\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"7a3beded-22d0-4984-a28b-cf8919e25ab8\",\"title\":\"བདེ་བ་ཅན་གྱི་བཀོད་པ།\",\"language\":\"bo\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"58f1542d-ae9e-4f58-a431-876c6a950e12\",\"title\":\"bde ba can gyi bkod pa\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"mainTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"2b669b89-626d-4632-aed1-111309b5ab79\",\"title\":\"The “shorter” Sukhāvatīvyūha (cf. the “longer,” Toh 49)\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"otherTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"afb3c3e8-00e9-46fa-af25-028347ac58a0\",\"title\":\"The Noble Mahāyāna Sūtra “The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī”\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"28f4ce7d-a789-4da3-a1c9-c0227fd775bd\",\"title\":\"Ārya­sukhāvatī­vyūha­nāma­mahā­yāna­sūtra\",\"language\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"7cdc5b34-9620-4b5a-9180-d259cc0e656d\",\"title\":\"’phags pa bde ba can gyi bkod pa zhes bya ba theg pa chen po’i mdo\",\"language\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"22717a43-0781-486e-9e7e-d6e831dad95c\",\"title\":\"འཕགས་པ་བདེ་བ་ཅན་གྱི་བཀོད་པ་ཞེས་བྱ་བ་ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོའི་མདོ།\",\"language\":\"bo\",\"type\":\"longTitle\"},{\"uuid\":\"b6b5f216-175c-4518-8723-3b2f8c2e01b5\",\"title\":\"Toh 115\",\"language\":\"en\",\"type\":\"toh\"}],\"frontMatter\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f74d9653-3e69-4b86-a95d-97d8acecff9d\",\"sort\":2,\"type\":\"summaryHeader\",\"label\":\"s.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":7,\"uuid\":\"5b3d3129-6dba-49b1-8f7a-4cca4b33dc68\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Summary\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":7}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a4511693-97ba-49b5-be92-b97cab8e530c\",\"sort\":4,\"type\":\"summary\",\"label\":\"s.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":457,\"uuid\":\"d429352d-4b33-4c77-93b1-3c8f389f8fdc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":3}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śrāvastī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":3,\"end\":11},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"61aa044f-aaea-4d30-b1ae-efbd23d8aaa4\",\"uuid\":\"693637f8-4093-4989-b421-451557f04036\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":11,\"end\":16}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Jeta’s Grove\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":16,\"end\":28},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"3f9da289-6926-4284-8fc0-c88a5c8710b8\",\"uuid\":\"fcf14cb0-06a2-4f49-b013-663839668262\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the Buddha Śākyamuni, surrounded by a large audience, presents to his disciple \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":28,\"end\":109}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":109,\"end\":118},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"9df8c472-5d31-4ed0-a8c5-78981a120bd0\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" a detailed description of the realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":118,\"end\":158}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":158,\"end\":167},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"3b34874a-f6bd-41b3-a658-43031a025c74\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", a delightful, enlightened abode, free of suffering. Its inhabitants are described as mature beings in an environment where everything enhances their spiritual inclinations. The principal buddha of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":167,\"end\":366}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":366,\"end\":375},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"f3032783-ec2f-45af-b0ba-5a75f02a78c8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is addressed as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":375,\"end\":392}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitāyus\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":392,\"end\":400},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"016abcba-d2ad-4141-a0c4-a1630608c46a\",\"uuid\":\"0588d734-30d2-443a-8f30-8352d440db96\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Limitless Life) as well as \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":400,\"end\":429}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":429,\"end\":437},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"f177933d-db4e-4dc7-bd4e-7d65fa5d789e\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Limitless Light). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":437,\"end\":457}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":457,\"end\":835,\"uuid\":\"58526d0f-6b6f-498d-9a5d-75c528e108dc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Buddha Śākyamuni further explains how virtuous people who focus single-mindedly on the Buddha \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":457,\"end\":555}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":555,\"end\":563},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"f5c017dc-2ddf-4c9b-9c96-45adfdbd95ae\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" will obtain a rebirth in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":563,\"end\":589}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":589,\"end\":598},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"3ca668cd-b9d0-41e5-8d99-d85ad5206e36\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" in their next life, and he urges all to develop faith in this teaching. In support, he cites the similar way in which the various buddhas of the six directions exhort their followers to develop confidence in this teaching on \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":598,\"end\":824}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":824,\"end\":833},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"f3e96e77-4406-49c4-b82a-5d46f1f3e228\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":833,\"end\":835}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":835,\"end\":990,\"uuid\":\"44a86c5a-0669-4e61-9cdd-4ca73cd5349c\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The sūtra ends with a short dialogue between \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":835,\"end\":880}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":880,\"end\":889},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"eb6625fa-58ab-4c92-bf01-6c4d01809240\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the Buddha Śākyamuni that highlights the difficulty of enlightened activity in a degenerate age.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":889,\"end\":990}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c38e2084-c999-4a50-a877-a8786d456870\",\"sort\":30,\"type\":\"acknowledgmentHeader\",\"label\":\"ac.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":15,\"uuid\":\"ac93f87f-314f-427c-b976-7298121d5861\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Acknowledgments\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c687acc9-8348-4781-8326-7d7fc59a2e06\",\"sort\":32,\"type\":\"acknowledgment\",\"label\":\"ac.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":266,\"uuid\":\"6afa8a1e-25f7-4f91-9d3c-1c8b0d32e20b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Translation by the Sakya Pandita Translation Group, International Buddhist Academy Division, Kathmandu, under the supervision of Khenpo Ngawang Jorden. This sūtra was translated into English by the monk Ngawang Rinchen Gyaltsen, Julia Stenzel, and Tsewang Gyaltsen. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":266}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":266,\"end\":384,\"uuid\":\"a711ef8a-07ae-41b3-b11b-e288dca0b637\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"This translation has been completed under the patronage and supervision of 84000: Translating the Words of the Buddha.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":266,\"end\":384}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a5dc4751-f136-4c81-b3b6-9e3081118957\",\"sort\":35,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"i.\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":12,\"uuid\":\"d73a2f9e-17e9-40ea-bfa9-1b46c2768542\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Introduction\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":12}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8649986b-ce1c-4512-bc8e-4b51414b71ab\",\"sort\":36,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":18,\"uuid\":\"bca0e23e-7a39-44df-984a-95a7a6b9c4a1\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Origin and History\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":18}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5dcadeea-8654-43cf-997f-acf495558f40\",\"sort\":38,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.1\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":444,\"uuid\":\"6c1a456a-173f-48ce-8e29-1258bab9928b\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":41},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"83774e28-3e11-418a-8cbd-344e3d373802\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is the shortest of three sūtras that expound the Land of Delight, the pure realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":41,\"end\":126}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":126,\"end\":134},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"9513530b-a79b-4eff-a96a-8ad689025506\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", called \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":134,\"end\":143}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":143,\"end\":152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"f73a73b3-7360-4d0a-b719-ae20cc5837c0\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The Kangyur includes Tibetan translations of two of these texts: this one, often called the “shorter” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":256}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":256,\"end\":265},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"46953f8f-eaef-46af-8f79-abacea7d97f3\",\"toh\":null,\"start\":256,\"end\":0}},{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cfa5f337-f6cb-4237-a6a2-fa60f014bffd\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and the “longer” sūtra, with the formal title \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":265,\"end\":313}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Array of Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":313,\"end\":334},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"8c0de1d0-2f5d-490b-a145-ab25cfbbe91a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Toh 49 in the Heap of Jewels section).\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":334,\"end\":374},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"ae7451ca-8305-41a6-93bb-33367b887e02\",\"label\":\"1\",\"uuid\":\"6e7a1589-bbe7-4091-bea8-3d35a0aa18ae\",\"start\":374,\"end\":374,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The third, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":374,\"end\":386}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Amitāyus Meditation Sūtra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":386,\"end\":415},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"90445680-fe75-4235-b65b-6f86a2d8e757\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":415,\"end\":416},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"ba07f770-0540-44e8-acd5-d6eae8b29962\",\"label\":\"2\",\"uuid\":\"b9414565-7dcd-49a5-b844-9f4deff6e1c0\",\"start\":416,\"end\":416,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is only extant in Chinese. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":416,\"end\":444}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":444,\"end\":635,\"uuid\":\"ff818bab-182a-4e50-ba9f-eb91f498a4af\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The shorter sūtra, according to the Sanskrit scholar Luis Gomez, first appeared in its written form during the first century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":444,\"end\":569}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":569,\"end\":571},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":569,\"end\":571,\"uuid\":\"cbf951f4-90f5-4dca-9e71-b8c2b4526942\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", possibly in what was then Northwest India and is now Pakistan.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":571,\"end\":635},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"cd485805-f6b1-40bb-9141-5ff6d5f50972\",\"label\":\"3\",\"uuid\":\"a57d889a-f816-4954-a222-09d590914375\",\"start\":635,\"end\":635,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"3758556c-bb65-438d-9adb-282176b0e35a\",\"sort\":58,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":32,\"uuid\":\"1d67e058-dca8-4fcc-8675-66c1999d41a6\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Source Text and Various Versions\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":32}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5a80817c-1d1c-48af-a59c-13a2898460a0\",\"sort\":60,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.2\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":439,\"uuid\":\"5a80817c-1d1c-48af-a59c-13a2898460a0\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"A Sanskrit version of the smaller \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":34}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":34,\"end\":71},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a595272c-137f-4d83-b1ce-8596caecbe64\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is extant today, as well as Tibetan and Chinese translations. All the translations show some variation from the Sanskrit source in content and style, which can be attributed in part to cultural and geographic conditions in Tibet and China.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":71,\"end\":311},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"16121895-52e7-4e90-b153-afcbf36b9d75\",\"label\":\"4\",\"uuid\":\"0408d97c-6343-43fa-88db-b601c6e19df2\",\"start\":311,\"end\":311,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" The translations have become more influential than the original itself, for which we presently lack any contextual information.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":311,\"end\":439}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"75d6cc52-a859-4d2d-9fc6-e92fc6d80d65\",\"sort\":66,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.3\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":765,\"uuid\":\"75d6cc52-a859-4d2d-9fc6-e92fc6d80d65\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There are several Chinese translations of this sūtra, dating from between 240 and 400 \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":86}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":88},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":86,\"end\":88,\"uuid\":\"a977f16e-fab0-4184-a459-c6f0ff84c26d\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", but only one Tibetan version, translated in the eighth or ninth century. The Chinese versions of the sūtra spread through China, Korea, Japan, and Vietnam and played an important role in the formation of the Pure Land schools in these countries. These versions appear to embellish the description of the wonders of the realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":88,\"end\":418}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":418,\"end\":427},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"798cf986-fa71-4e85-b6ab-591737104aba\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\",\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":427,\"end\":428},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"da8db36e-72fc-4ec6-8500-69586f52842c\",\"label\":\"5\",\"uuid\":\"b7fa1621-f2aa-4607-9a5d-b1ac113b9267\",\"start\":428,\"end\":428,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" whereas the Tibetan version is more subdued and shows its main variations from the Sanskrit original in the names and the number of buddhas presiding over the different buddha realms. The various editions in the Tibetan canon, i.e., the Degé, Narthang, Peking, and Lhasa editions, show no major differences that would alter any meaning.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":428,\"end\":765}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a7c7597-658d-4d29-a4d2-1202a542da9f\",\"sort\":74,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.4\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":435,\"uuid\":\"0a7c7597-658d-4d29-a4d2-1202a542da9f\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"For the present translation, we have followed the Tibetan text, while comparing it with the Sanskrit original. Concerning the enumeration of names of the buddhas presiding over the various buddha realms, we have retained their original Sanskrit names, unless the Tibetan text had names without a known Sanskrit equivalent, in which case we chose to translate those names into English. The differences are further commented on in notes.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":435}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"513ea6ba-2fad-4112-9b57-9be8a3fd6372\",\"sort\":76,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.5\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":198,\"uuid\":\"513ea6ba-2fad-4112-9b57-9be8a3fd6372\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Tibetan version of the smaller \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":35}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":35,\"end\":72},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a3421ce4-a8f2-43f6-9729-71d1a00b72d8\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" was translated by the Indian preceptor \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":72,\"end\":112}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Dānaśīla\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":112,\"end\":120},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"cc129426-225c-49dd-9d7d-d38b5291a7bb\",\"uuid\":\"fbce9196-9fc5-4d69-9cc4-14c25b61d8da\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the chief editor-translator \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":120,\"end\":153}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Bandé Yeshé Dé\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":153,\"end\":167},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"2b04d627-b147-4363-9cc0-bf9ae96a744e\",\"uuid\":\"6f357615-c3ba-4194-a270-0360f517b8b1\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", as indicated in the colophon.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":167,\"end\":198}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"a58c9a82-52cb-4bdc-9460-007d3dc50466\",\"sort\":83,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"7f92f055-9e2e-45be-ba3c-7eff200b278f\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Main Points of the Subject Matter\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0f0d0877-a783-4bc1-a1f3-966e37f2a5d6\",\"sort\":85,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.6\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":633,\"uuid\":\"8e555ad0-e4fd-4c8d-b612-b8095998401d\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The sūtra’s overall subject is revealed in the title. The Sanskrit term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":72}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":72,\"end\":81},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":72,\"end\":81,\"uuid\":\"d470bdd9-056e-4708-8f86-202c23c2fa7a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}},{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"48106790-690a-477e-bc63-3bc04ae6b626\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", in Tibetan Dewachen (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":81,\"end\":104}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bde ba can\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":114},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":104,\"end\":114,\"uuid\":\"c6f6cec6-8ccf-419a-bca6-805a429ba4bc\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), designates a realm of delight, a place where no suffering is experienced. The inhabitants of this realm are spiritually advanced beings who enjoy the presence of buddhas, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":114,\"end\":288}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bodhisattvas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":288,\"end\":300},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b\",\"uuid\":\"b6c2cfea-3817-479b-9ad3-eb1bb926d7d9\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":300,\"end\":306}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"arhats\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":306,\"end\":312},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"69c51647-a349-4599-ae95-dbde5c407416\",\"uuid\":\"f82283df-2917-4590-8bd7-04536efef23f\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", and engage exclusively in wholesome activities. The principal buddha of this realm has two names, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":312,\"end\":412}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitāyus\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":412,\"end\":420},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"016abcba-d2ad-4141-a0c4-a1630608c46a\",\"uuid\":\"528d01e2-68fc-46ab-9940-390c996d49d8\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Limitless Life) and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":420,\"end\":442}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":442,\"end\":450},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"1f499f2f-3c96-48c7-8f7e-54094d56d6e3\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Limitless Light). Even though it is not explicitly stated in this particular sūtra, \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":450,\"end\":536}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitāyus\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":536,\"end\":544},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"016abcba-d2ad-4141-a0c4-a1630608c46a\",\"uuid\":\"2904d016-3cee-4966-82f1-c6de106c9c80\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" is, in Vajrayāna contexts, sometimes considered a sambhogakāya form of Buddha \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":544,\"end\":623}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":623,\"end\":631},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"c1f5477c-e4c3-491d-8aea-883eec031730\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\".\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":631,\"end\":632},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"endNoteLink\",\"attrs\":{\"notes\":[{\"endNote\":\"4be4c72e-7d7c-40ff-ade4-7cbb35e1ffe8\",\"label\":\"6\",\"uuid\":\"af185838-4ad0-4d6c-8282-51bd754ee922\",\"start\":632,\"end\":632,\"location\":\"end\",\"toh\":null}]}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":632,\"end\":633}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":633,\"end\":987,\"uuid\":\"1c7d5ae3-cd01-40d4-b824-ca8132f96a66\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The term \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":633,\"end\":642}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"vyūha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":647},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":642,\"end\":647,\"uuid\":\"1c1fa5dd-a5d6-4031-a9fb-38f5570a960c\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Sa-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (Tib. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":647,\"end\":654}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bkod pa\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":654,\"end\":661},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":654,\"end\":661,\"uuid\":\"fe89de2b-8c37-4fdb-b7c4-057513c1fbbf\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") means “display,” indicating that the sūtra is to a large extent a description of this buddha realm and its characteristics. It is a land with lakes and forests full of jewels, with magical birds, and with little bells producing lovely sounds. Its ideal environment enhances the spiritual practice of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":661,\"end\":963}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":963,\"end\":972},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"afc56a31-2d4d-4c0a-be77-5af828d2afc5\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s inhabitants.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":972,\"end\":987}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"891f4adc-5ec5-4783-a658-912f7cb8b0df\",\"sort\":110,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":16,\"uuid\":\"7313535b-82a4-4fd6-81fe-cf7fe0531aa3\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Four Main Topics\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":16}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"57fac4f9-dda8-4bc4-add5-b99fefac9309\",\"sort\":112,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.7\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":230,\"uuid\":\"57fac4f9-dda8-4bc4-add5-b99fefac9309\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The sūtra contains four main topics: (1) the description of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":60}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":60,\"end\":69},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"797067f3-d8f4-43d5-a384-7b1474c6b434\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"; (2) the prerequisites needed to take birth in this realm; (3) praise of this discourse expressed by other buddhas; and (4) the Buddha Śākyamuni’s supreme feat.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":69,\"end\":230}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"46271cff-2de8-41a9-bf1f-5825f7a6b6fb\",\"sort\":115,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":11,\"uuid\":\"4d8ed4e2-699f-4fe4-9068-1534b36cd998\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Setting\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":11}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2c506638-66fa-4ec5-b69e-20417e51a858\",\"sort\":117,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.8\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":502,\"uuid\":\"f0a89762-5c3e-43bf-931e-77bb6b6e0aa5\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The narrative of the sūtra takes place in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":42}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śrāvastī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":50},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"61aa044f-aaea-4d30-b1ae-efbd23d8aaa4\",\"uuid\":\"96a6c3b3-1be1-44a5-9711-8b34f69daa78\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", in \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":50,\"end\":55}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍada’s Park\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":55,\"end\":89},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"3f9da289-6926-4284-8fc0-c88a5c8710b8\",\"uuid\":\"c0ad5079-11d2-4d9e-b858-8caab97ab825\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", where the Buddha Śākyamuni, in the presence of a large audience consisting of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":89,\"end\":169}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"arhats\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":169,\"end\":175},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"69c51647-a349-4599-ae95-dbde5c407416\",\"uuid\":\"6ba67d03-dfc3-4fef-94a3-4890f7d6fc27\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":175,\"end\":180}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bodhisattvas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":180,\"end\":192},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b\",\"uuid\":\"dd140578-034a-4ad3-8c7f-ac3235a7798c\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", addresses his disciple \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":192,\"end\":217}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":217,\"end\":226},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"2040cd83-6fb7-47e0-a917-18dca1e56960\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and tells him about the realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":226,\"end\":260}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":260,\"end\":269},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"562adb33-895b-49a4-b3d2-64f02dc27949\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". The sūtra is in large part a discourse spoken by the Buddha. Even though the Buddha regularly asks the question, “\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":269,\"end\":385}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":385,\"end\":394},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"34f3e38a-9dbd-4af5-8721-06305eb0ddbd\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", what do you think about this?” \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":394,\"end\":427}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":427,\"end\":436},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"5029bb87-1d78-4898-a27d-9d11fd1d1799\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" speaks only at the very end of the sūtra and praises the Buddha. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":436,\"end\":502}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":502,\"end\":697,\"uuid\":\"27b4f562-71b8-474d-91c3-ff9c228a0af3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The sūtra ends with a short dialogue between \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":502,\"end\":547}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śāriputra\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":547,\"end\":556},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"135f3abf-9fb4-4595-950f-afc4d377f8d3\",\"uuid\":\"67508e91-d9eb-4d13-9be2-cbb6b07caa17\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" and the Buddha Śākyamuni that highlights the difficulty of the Buddha Śākyamuni’s attaining enlightenment and preaching in a degenerate age.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":556,\"end\":697}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"06498ba7-0774-41de-9092-d19d1c082450\",\"sort\":137,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":33,\"uuid\":\"9632bc0a-9070-4eac-b0f3-0f57da9e3ec0\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Significance of Buddha Realms\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":33}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e5fcda2c-693a-4125-a37b-6076ec989ce0\",\"sort\":139,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.9\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":241,\"uuid\":\"c606b54b-09c4-4ba1-8b30-0c2a7f8d31e9\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The notion of innumerable buddha realms coexisting with our reality became popular with the emergence of Mahāyāna Buddhism around the first century \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":148}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"ᴄᴇ\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":150},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"smallCaps\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":148,\"end\":150,\"uuid\":\"14ed9b39-f672-4c62-8922-697560389c3a\",\"type\":\"span\",\"textStyle\":\"small-caps\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". They have been interchangeably translated as buddhafields, buddha realms, or pure lands. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":150,\"end\":241}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":241,\"end\":738,\"uuid\":\"c5828e97-6aab-4068-8136-b9d69f676ea7\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":241,\"end\":244}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":244,\"end\":285},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"c56b274a-0450-4d4c-afb4-27fe2352d438\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", the Land of Delight is described as a realm beyond space and time. The two larger sūtras elaborate on the history of its emergence. According to those sūtras, the Land of Delight is the result of the powerful vows of the Buddha \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":285,\"end\":515}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":515,\"end\":523},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"18e69f49-a55d-4647-aba3-5132f982548d\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", who out of great compassion created a safe environment for fortunate beings to progress toward spiritual maturity. The smaller sūtra, however, refers only to the existence of such a realm and its characteristics. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":523,\"end\":738}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":738,\"end\":985,\"uuid\":\"252762c7-b4b0-4042-b944-bac1ba9396ea\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"In this sūtra, the Buddha Śākyamuni explains the manner in which beings take birth in this realm: fortunate sons and daughters are told to accumulate a significant amount of merit and direct their faith single-mindedly toward the Buddha \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":738,\"end\":975}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":975,\"end\":983},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"4a57df1f-03a8-4ede-915b-bbe913b4c590\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":983,\"end\":985}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":985,\"end\":1206,\"uuid\":\"d5ecbb3a-d4e0-49a2-87cf-ef1b584ed1bc\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Śākyamuni’s discourse mentions an alternative title for this sūtra. He explains that there are countless buddha realms with \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":985,\"end\":1109}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"tathāgatas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1109,\"end\":1119},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"112ee268-cc96-43d6-9b25-3c948f36e0e5\",\"uuid\":\"872ffd34-b3d2-4c60-8fdf-ed99df5bcdda\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" who praise \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1119,\"end\":1131}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1131,\"end\":1140},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"f855a162-0743-45c4-8570-d9e3c130cff6\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" with a Dharma discourse called “Complete Embrace by All Buddhas.”\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1140,\"end\":1206}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"0a1a0df5-5187-4c80-ba95-1b2c21da5718\",\"sort\":155,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":44,\"uuid\":\"34279162-ee3b-46d0-ae71-e5ee4f6afb8c\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"References to the Sūtra in the Tibetan Canon\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":44}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"2febce7c-2c9d-4835-9179-37828cda4973\",\"sort\":157,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.10\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":284,\"uuid\":\"5d36552a-f3e3-446a-94c3-1092555e8ad3\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The various sūtras of the Pure Land of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":39}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":39,\"end\":48},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"0c4bebf6-7dea-4ce7-8c80-e6b067ab1659\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" have inspired Tibetan masters to write prayers and practice rituals that allow adepts to enter \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":48,\"end\":144}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":144,\"end\":152},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"e4bade85-4037-4f80-875d-10dd956f5c60\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’s realm. There are numerous \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":152,\"end\":181}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":181,\"end\":190},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"3ec0178c-ecb7-46bc-8722-27393cacc6db\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"-related compositions available in the Tengyur and in different collected works (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":190,\"end\":271}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"gsung ’bum\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":271,\"end\":281},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"5e9148bf-0e5e-4e94-a15d-21a5c1291aa0\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":281,\"end\":284}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":570,\"uuid\":\"e49eb848-6e63-4de2-82a0-1c038b83e8e1\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Collection of Prayers for Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":284,\"end\":323},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"70b7e3d1-9c63-4ad9-aa72-9d0f96b58213\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":323,\"end\":325}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bde smon phyogs bsgrigs\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":325,\"end\":348},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"f3c5bc17-4bb3-40d1-8d2f-d708ee418bc5\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\") is a collection of prayers, practice rituals, and commentaries concerning the pure land of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":348,\"end\":441}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":441,\"end\":449},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"c82b4eff-c667-4f18-b846-ff0ac6abbf42\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". An edition was published in Chengdu in 2007 by Sichuan Minorities Publishing House (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":449,\"end\":535}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Si khron mi rigs dpe skrun khang\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":535,\"end\":567},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":535,\"end\":567,\"uuid\":\"3ca549a2-d31e-4143-9ecb-67eabea95e9b\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":567,\"end\":570}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":570,\"end\":820,\"uuid\":\"cd504dd5-691d-4a6f-b80a-c6ba63943f70\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"One of the Tibetan masters who made \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":570,\"end\":606}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":606,\"end\":615},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"2d5c72fe-46bf-48d0-8164-c99f45335451\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" a particular focus of attention was Chagmé Rinpoché (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":615,\"end\":669}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’chags med\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":669,\"end\":679},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":669,\"end\":679,\"uuid\":\"ca6a4d0e-47be-4a5c-8f91-a0ea824ec661\",\"type\":\"span\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"textStyle\":\"foreign\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\", 1610–78). He composed \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":679,\"end\":703}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Long Prayer of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":703,\"end\":731},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"11417600-cdea-41a4-b086-87c7500af086\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":731,\"end\":733}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"mkhas grub rā ga a syas mdzad pa’i rnam dag bde chen zhing gi smon lam\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":733,\"end\":803},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"e122179c-5bce-4fc9-b2ba-503d34802e30\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), among others. \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":803,\"end\":820}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":820,\"end\":1159,\"uuid\":\"16955619-c558-474d-82c6-5537bf4b5475\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Furthermore, the well-known \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":820,\"end\":848}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Noble King of Prayers for Good Conduct\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":848,\"end\":886},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"596a6b40-67c7-4ca5-9cdd-0d8fb54d846f\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" (\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":886,\"end\":888}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"’phags pa bzang po spyod pa’i smon lam gyi rgyal po\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":888,\"end\":939},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7098bce1-d8c5-45cd-b0d3-e6b44ecfe174\",\"lang\":\"Bo-Ltn\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"), recited by adherents of all Tibetan schools, concludes with the aspiration for rebirth in the pure realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":939,\"end\":1050}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1050,\"end\":1059},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"8cf35b98-d3a2-4bb5-b2f7-1a95c6bd693e\",\"uuid\":\"42d7b08d-4d4a-425d-8b77-389a2bfe4afa\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". Praying to be born in the pure realm of \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1059,\"end\":1101}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Amitābha\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1101,\"end\":1109},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"019bfc76-b305-413a-8827-05de2cde5ac5\",\"uuid\":\"50ab7dc2-0761-45f0-b175-ff9cc7c09cbd\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" has become a major practice in Mahāyāna Buddhism.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":1109,\"end\":1159}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"b8efb62d-2e5a-472e-abda-6fe0fdb2e369\",\"sort\":192,\"type\":\"introductionHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":3,\"start\":0,\"end\":17,\"uuid\":\"8732886f-1dae-4a16-94e5-062707055c73\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Academic Research\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":17}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"cfcda873-00f4-4a31-9fbe-684b5929b960\",\"sort\":194,\"type\":\"introduction\",\"label\":\"i.11\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":271,\"uuid\":\"435ae8be-7ea0-4aed-81a4-988e28d12bcf\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"There appears to have been no translation of the Tibetan \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":57}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":57,\"end\":94},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"italic\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"359554cd-d132-4197-b399-86c5bed9cd2a\",\"lang\":\"en\",\"type\":\"inlineTitle\"}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\" prior to the one published here. However, the Sanskrit version of the sūtra was translated into English and edited by Max Müller and Bunyiu Nanjio in Müller and Nanjio (1883). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":94,\"end\":271}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":271,\"end\":767,\"uuid\":\"1be72116-c00b-4f6d-b61b-14fe14a2c158\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Luis O. Gomez has published a nonliteral, poetic translation of the Sanskrit and Chinese versions of the smaller and larger sūtras and gives an introduction to the main topics (Gomez 1996). His literal translation of the same sūtras is forthcoming. Hisao Inagaki has translated the three Pure Land sūtras on the basis of their Chinese versions; this translation appears in the BDK English Tripiṭaka Vol. 12, Berkeley, 1995. An earlier translation from the Chinese was published in Utsuki (1924). \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":271,\"end\":767}}]},{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":767,\"end\":902,\"uuid\":\"f9c9baf4-b34f-45f5-aa18-819287c53b2a\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Nakamura (1987) presents an historical introduction to the beginnings of Pure Land Buddhism and its textual sources in Indian Buddhism.\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":767,\"end\":902}}]}]}],\"body\":[{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"30b67060-a712-46ba-87dd-126ae1a7a1df\",\"sort\":203,\"type\":\"translationHeader\",\"label\":\"\",\"alignments\":{}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"level\":2,\"start\":0,\"end\":15,\"uuid\":\"75d00be2-e612-4274-81db-779f4d1077a9\",\"class\":\"section-title\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Translation\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":15}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"290690fe-3622-44f8-9b07-5c5d13538062\",\"sort\":204,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.\",\"alignments\":{\"toh115\":{\"folioUuid\":\"9a932216-0d1b-4be8-aabf-e09cee1df018\",\"toh\":\"toh115\",\"tibetan\":\"༄༅། །རྒྱ་གར་སྐད་དུ། ཨཱརྱ་སུ་ཁ་བ་ཏི་བྱཱུ་ཧནཱ་མ་མ་ཧཱ་ཡཱ་ན་སཱུ་ཏྲ། བོད་སྐད་དུ། འཕགས་པ་བདེ་བ་ཅན་གྱི་བཀོད་པ་ཞེས་བྱ་བ་ཐེག་པ་ཆེན་པོའི་མདོ། \",\"folioNumber\":195,\"volumeNumber\":51}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25,\"uuid\":\"fc67143f-0efb-4603-94bd-77b2f3789ec7\",\"level\":2,\"class\":\"body-title-honorific\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"611bafa6-d5a3-4096-8608-b31bb2bd16d2\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Noble Mahāyāna Sūtra \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":25}}]},{\"type\":\"heading\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":66,\"uuid\":\"5ad4e4a4-f524-433a-819e-8939cde3df6e\",\"level\":2,\"class\":\"body-title-main\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The Display of the Pure Land of Sukhāvatī\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":25,\"end\":66}}]}]},{\"type\":\"passage\",\"attrs\":{\"uuid\":\"7f12c74e-7191-42d0-8d7f-a89ce8dcf714\",\"sort\":206,\"type\":\"translation\",\"label\":\"1.1\",\"alignments\":{\"toh115\":{\"folioUuid\":\"9a932216-0d1b-4be8-aabf-e09cee1df018\",\"toh\":\"toh115\",\"tibetan\":\"$25\",\"folioNumber\":195,\"volumeNumber\":51}}},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"paragraph\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":44,\"uuid\":\"c19104a5-db34-432e-89c7-8e46e6c71b7e\",\"hasLeadingSpace\":true,\"leadingSpaceUuid\":\"500cd91a-a0fe-41a1-ae00-af8f580860fd\"},\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Homage to all the buddhas and \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":0,\"end\":30}},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"bodhisattvas\",\"attrs\":{\"start\":30,\"end\":42},\"marks\":[{\"type\":\"glossaryInstance\",\"attrs\":{\"glossary\":\"12b57130-bc88-464a-8262-901983c0510b\",\"uuid\":\"cf8c8aa9-fbf7-4d76-9d1a-575c56248929\",\"toh\":null}}]},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\". \",\"attrs\":{\"start\":42,\"end\":44}}]},{\"type\":\"paragrap